Pt had itching about 50 minutes after getting the Pfizer covid vaccine. Pt waited the time requested and was thankfully still shopping with her mother and brother in the store when the reaction developed. Pt was given 50mg of liquid diphenhydramine. I discussed calling 911 with the family and they said they would prefer we did not if possible. She has food allergies, which were discussed before giving the vaccine and she is used to having reactions, she also knows what anaphylaxis feels like and could tell that was not the reaction she was having. After discussing with the family and consulting with my market direction I decided to not call 911 immediately but let them know that if the diphenhydramine was not helping quickly I would make the call. I observed the patient for 30+ minutes with an EpiPen on my person in case she showed any signs of worsening. She improved visibly while getting drowsy from the antihistamine. After she had stabilized for some time and the patient and her family was also comfortable with her improvement I allowed her to depart the pharmacy with a request to keep her EpiPen close and call 911 if things worsen or the EpiPen became necessary.

Patient was observed post Covid-19 immunization for 30 minutes based on pre-vaccination screening .  During the observation period, she experienced an adverse reaction with the following symptoms:  Tingling to tongue, phlegm to back of throat, tingling inside of mouth.   Assessment : Time of assessment 1205  Alert and oriented. Patient reported after 25 minutes of a 30 minute observation feeling tingling to the inside of her mouth, the tip of her tongue tingling and phlegm to the back of the throat. She denies difficulty swallowing (drinking water), no rashes, no swelling of tongue noted.    Actions taken: Vaers form completed, medications given, observed additional 30 minutes.   There were no vitals filed for this visit.   Medications administered: 1212-Benadryl 12.5 mg elixir by RN; 1215- Pepcid 20 mg po by RN as approved by RN (medication available not scored, so the whole 20 mg tablet given). After 5 minutes per protocol to give additional 12.5 mg Benadryl, patient refused 2nd dose and says she's starting to feel better.   Disposition: After additional 30 minutes observation, patient reports no tingling to tip of tongue and inside of mouth has no tingling. She says the phlegm is still there, but not as much. She is discharged to go home and advised to follow up with her PCP about the symptoms due to she reported after 1st dose when she was going home, she had the same sensation of tingling to the mouth/tongue. I advised to call 911 if symptoms return, she verbalized understanding. Advised to buy some Benadryl liquid to take if needed as instructed by PCP.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient reported feeling weakness/nauseous and asked to lay down. Patient was assisted to exam bed. Symptoms started approximately 15 minutes post-injection. Patient reported not eating lunch meal, and felt weakness, dizziness and explained she had a previous event similar to this with a flu vaccine approximately 15-20 years ago. No loss of consciousness. Initial Vitals BP 108/72, HR 68, RR and 98% SaO2. After rest, some oral intake of fluids and 30 minutes of discussion, patient felt better and was asymptomatic except for pain at the injection site. No dyspnea, no audible wheezing or breathing restriction and no other symptoms beside near syncopal episode. Patient explained she does not do well with needles. Feeling nauseous, warm & sweaty post vaccination. Sit down on bed, rested given crackers & water, felt better. Vitals recorded, given crackers, water, took vitals, felt better, after lying down and resting. Patient reported previous similar symptoms w/previous flu shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I awoke at 3am with splitting headache. Took a Tylonol and went back to bed. In the morning I awoke with headache, body aches, temperature of 100.3 and very fatigued. After eating something I went back to bed until dinner time. The next day I felt fine. The day later, 2/16/21, I again had the same symptoms but milder and again slept most of the day. Since then the mild headache and fatigue have returned everyday in the late afternoon until a week ago, April 1, 2021. On March 24, I visited Dr. on another issue and asked if my symptoms could be a residual from the vaccine. He said yes and I told me to report my symptoms on this site. I no longer have any lingering symptoms.

First vaccine on 03/12/2021: Noted injection site pain and swelling, fatigue, foggy mentally on day 2. All slowly resolved by day 5. Day 8, 03/20/2021: Itching of head, arms, and chest. Felt general malaise, and lightheaded with movement or any activity.  Day 9, 03/21/2021: Injection site erythema and swelling greater than 15 cm.  Day 10, 03/22/2021: PETECHIAE of lower extremities from uper thighs to ankles.  Day 12, 03/24/2021: First sign of improvement. Itching less, slightly less erythema at infection site, less lightheadedness with some increase in number of PETECHIAE. Continued to feel physically restricted.  At no time was there a fever, chills, or typical headache. However, there was occasional mild nausea,  Continued from page 1: and one migraine aura. Day 13, 03/25/2021: Appointment with local Internist who agreed with findings during his physical exam. Dx : "CUTANEOUS SMALL VESSEL VASCULITIS". Tx: Rest, observation, Labs, Avoid 2nd vaccine dose,  go to the emergency department with worsening of any signs or symptoms.  Day 14, 03/26/2021: No increase in the number of PETECHIAE. Day 15 to Day 25, 03/27/2021 to 04/5/2021: All signs and symptoms slowly resolving. Labs performed on  on 03/31/2021 at Day 19 were reported to all  be within normal limits on 04/02/2021.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Lightheaded; almost fainted; dizzy; dizziness; Almost passed out; Very light headache; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 67-year-old male patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE; Lot Number: EL9263), via an unspecified route of administration in left arm (shoulder), on 26Jan2021 at 12:00, at a single dose, for COVID-19 immunization. The patient's medical history included blood pressure, acid reflux, and multivitamin. The patient's concomitant medications included amlodipine for blood pressure, esomeprazole for acid reflux, and ascorbic acid/ biotin/ boron/ calcium/ calcium pantothenate/ chloride/ chromium/ colecalciferol/ copper/ cyanocobalamin/ folic acid/ iodine/ lycopene/ magnesium/ manganese/ molybdenum/ nickel/ nicotinamide/ phosphorus/ phytomenadione/ potassium/ pyridoxine hydrochloride/ retinol acetate/ riboflavin/ selenium/ silicon dioxide/ sodium metavanadate/ thiamine mononitrate/ tocopheryl acetate/ xantofyl/ zinc (CENTRUM SILVER ADULTS 50+) as multivitamin, all were ongoing; omeprazole for acid reflux; and an unspecified multivitamin.  The patient really had no issues going on prior to onset of these events. The patient has been administered both first and second doses of Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccines. The patient had been having some strange things that he didn't know if its COVID-19 shot related but they're symptoms he never had before. About 8 to 11 days after first dose of the vaccine (Feb2021; maybe 09Feb2021 or 10Feb2021), the patient had a very, very lightheaded episode where he almost passed out or almost fainted. The patient clarified he thinks one event was like 8 days and the other was like 10 days after the vaccine doses were administered, but is not sure, so left it as about 8 to 11 days. Also, in Feb2021, the patient had almost a very light headache where he almost fainted. The patient went to the emergency room in Feb2021 and was admitted to hospital from about 13:00 that day, overnight and discharged about 17:00 to 18:00 the following day. The patient spent the night in hospital, they sent him the next day. While in hospital (Feb2021), the patient had electrocardiograms (EKGs) of his head (as reported), magnetic resonance imaging (MRIs) of his head, computed tomography (CTs; CT scan with contrast) of his head, and echocardiograms of his heart (microcardiogram). All of those tests came back normal (okay), nothing abnormal on results. They were relating this to a stroke-like symptom; however, the results were normal, also his blood test results were fine. The patient had blood work done the first time he was in the emergency room when he was admitted to the hospital in Feb2021; they took his blood 3 to 4 times while he was there overnight and blood work results all came back normal. The patient was not sure what they were testing for, but thinks they were looking for stroke type things because the event almost made him pass out. They did not draw more blood the second emergency room visit. Because of the first episode, the patient then went to his family doctor and the doctor ordered some other testing done. The patient was scheduled to get a nuclear stress test and an exercise stress test (stress test of heart), his results on 10Mar2021 came back normal (not performed until after the second reported event following second dose of Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine). The patient believed that the results of those tests both came back good, family doctor emailed him the results which were normal. The patient was continuing to have some lightheaded episodes or symptoms just about daily but nothing really; continued to have symptoms which was not normal for him. Sometimes, they last for 30 minutes or more, multiple times a day. Sometimes, the patient had a good day, but he had those lightheaded episodes and he never had it before he got the shot. As therapeutic measures in the hospital, the emergency room gave the patient something for dizziness when he was there, but he was no longer taking it. Currently, the patient was really taking nothing. The patient had also gone to the ear, nose, and throat (ENT) doctor where he had a balance test or a videonystagmography (VNG) test done on 17Mar2021. The patient will get results of balance test on Wednesday (24Mar2021). Every year (unspecified), the patient goes and get his yearly test in which they had his blood work done and this and his glucose levels were always good, cholesterol level was always good. All the patient's other tests come back as normal on an unspecified date. The patient had never had these symptoms before, he hasn't changed his medications or habits and it's odd that this happened 9 to 10 days after both doses of the vaccine. The patient would like to know if this has been reported before as a side effect related to the vaccine. The patient was not sure if the events are Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine related, but they never happened to him before those doses were administered. He does not know if this is vaccine related or just coincidence that they popped up at the same time as the vaccine doses. Also, he does not know if events could be age related, the medical community can't figure it out so he is trying to get information on if events could be related to the vaccines. So the patient doesn't know if anybody else is reporting this but he had 2 sorts of severe episodes both of them around days after each shot and he was continuing to have lightheaded episodes but not severe as those 2 but he had lightheaded (dizzy) episodes daily, since the COVID-19 vaccine. But they didn't know what brought these episodes on, other than timing wise it was during the COVID-19 shot. And he never had anything like that, and he was not blaming it on the COVID-10 shot. That was the only thing changed in his lifestyle. There might be a possibility, because that's the only thing changed, his medication has not changed, and diet doesn't change. Nothing has changed other than the patient got COVID-19 shots. The patient wanted to report it, so the company had a report file and other people reporting it. The patient wanted to know if the company was having any other report or something like this so that he would know if it might be related to the shot. The patient had not recovered from "Lightheaded; almost fainted; dizzy; dizziness". The outcome of the other events was unknown.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Community health worker came to this RN, after several attempts made to check patient was unsuccessful.  It was subsequently realized she 14yrs/10mos. and should not have been vaccinated.  Upon hearing this, this RN realized that she had personally administered this vaccine. RN immediately notified Dr who felt that in the next few months this age group would be included in the vaccine, and that someone, "with more authority than he" should determine if patient is to get her 2nd dose as this was not scheduled. This RN spoke directly to patient's mother, asking, "what prompted her to bring patient realizing that she was only 14 y'o'?"  Mom stated, "I received a note from the school telling me that it was ok so I brought her".  This RN shared that we must get our information from the scientist/researchers/health care experts and government on when this age would be included and that as a part of the team, she should have waited until she heard this on a news station that she could trust to which she agreed. This RN shared that patient will surely benefit from some degree of immunity for this 1st dose, and responded that she is not clear if she will need 2 or just one dose when her time comes per the moms question. RN met w/ clinic manager to discuss how processes not people failed to work in this instance and that we would develop a process to ensure that this does not occur again.  Met w/ CHW who signed her  in and shared the same content r/t creating a new process.  Again, shared w/ AAC Director as well.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: acute dementia improved in an unbelievable way; acute dementia; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient's daughter) from a Pfizer-sponsored program. A 96-year-old female patient received bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE), dose 1 via an unspecified route of administration on an unspecified date (Batch/Lot number was not reported) as a single dose, dose 2 via an unspecified route of administration on an unspecified date (Batch/Lot number was not reported) as a single dose for COVID-19 immunization. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On an unspecified date, the patient experienced acute dementia (medically significant), and acute dementia improved in an unbelievable way (medically significant). The clinical course was reported as follows: The patient's daughter wanted to report that after receiving two doses of the COVID vaccine, the patient's "acute dementia improved in an unbelievable way." The patient went from being nonverbal and inarticulate, to becoming articulate and reading short words; something the patient's daughter had not seen in two years at least. The patient's daughter reported that there was only one change in her environment, which was the vaccine. The patient's daughter wanted to share her story and hoped this could help others. The patient's daughter stated: "I've seen anecdotal evidence and am amazed." The clinical outcome of the event, acute dementia, was recovering. The clinical outcome of the event, unexpected beneficial therapeutic response, was unknown.  The batch/lot numbers for the vaccine, bnt162b2, were not provided and will be requested during follow up.

Preterm delivery at 32.7 weeks of gestational age; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This observational study case was received on 14-Dec-2020 from other health professional and concerned a 32-year-old pregnant, female subject of body weight 272.5 lbs, height 67 inches and body mass index (BMI) 42.7, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with Afluria QIV, a seasonal quadrivalent vaccine, during pregnancy.   The subject's concurrent conditions included obesity, uterine fibroids and asthma. The subject's concomitant medication included Prenatal plus DHA (unspecified vitamins, minerals and docosahexaenoic acid) used for pregnancy.  The subject's obstetrical history included one previous pregnancy with one full-term live birth. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM). Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with MCM. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was reported as 20-Jun-2020. The subject's estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 27-Mar-2021 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 07-Apr-2021. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 18-Aug-2020, the ultrasound revealed no MCM.  On 11-Sep-2020, at approximately 11 weeks of gestation (calculated per LMP), the subject was vaccinated with Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL) (influenza vaccine, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported) (explicitly coded as 'vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was P100230203.  On the same day, the ultrasound revealed no MCM.  On 25-Nov-2020, the ultrasound revealed no MCM.  At gestational age of 32.7 weeks (as reported), the subject delivered a premature live, male neonate via caesarean method. The neonate's birth weight was 2231 grams, head circumference was 30.5 cm, and body length was 47 cm. Appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 5 (one minute), 6 (five minutes) and 8 (ten minutes). No MCM was identified at birth. The obesity complicating childbirth was marked as pregnancy complication.   The outcome of the event 'premature delivery' was not reported.   The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  The event of 'premature delivery' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  This case is linked to case 202102139 (the corresponding neonate's case).  Additional information received on 26-Mar-2021 from other health professional: Pregnancy outcome received. The event 'premature delivery' added and case upgraded to serious. Stop date for the event 'vaccine exposure during pregnancy' added and outcome for this event changed from 'not reported' to 'resolved'. Narrative amended accordingly.  Company comment: The event of 'vaccine exposure during pregnancy' is considered as not related to Afluria QIV.  Company comment: A 32-year-old subject was administered with Afluria QIV, at gestational age of 11 weeks. On 15-Feb-2021, at gestational age of 32.7 weeks, the subject delivered a premature live, male neonate via caesarean method. The subject's concurrent conditions included obesity, uterine fibroids and asthma. Causal role of the suspect vaccine is assessed as not related, due to biological implausibility and strong confounder from medical history (uterine fibroids). Soft tissue infection; Still having problems using his arm; Elbow was huge and swollen, moved up towards the injection site; Rendered elbow immobile; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer (patient), concerning himself, a 76 years-old male patient, unknown race and ethnicity, who was administered Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273), and experienced soft tissue infection, knot under the skin below the elbow which has increased in size (soft tissue swelling), elbow was huge and swollen, moved up towards the injection site (joint swelling), still having problems using his arm (vaccination site movement impairment), area under his elbow was huge and swollen/moved towards injection site (joint swelling), and rendered elbow immobile (joint disorder).  The patient's medical history was not reported. Concomitant medications reported were unspecified blood thinners, unknown medications for heart and high blood pressure.  On 27 Jan 2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received the first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (lot/batch: unknown) intramuscular in upper right arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  The consumer stated that the events started from 30 Jan 2021. He noticed a knot under the skin below his elbow. The patient stated that he rubbed alcohol on the injection site in the spot on his elbow to see if it would help. The next morning, on 31 Jan 2021, the area under his elbow has increased in size, was huge and swollen, rendered elbow muscle. It had moved up towards the injection site and was about five inches long by two-three inches long. The consumer stated that he had met with urgent care via video and they think that it could be in the lymph nodes. The consumer stated that the doctor wrote him a prescription for an antibiotic to treat a soft tissue infection, but he has not picked it up yet. The consumer stated he was still having problems using his arm. Treatment medications included was ibuprofen, acetaminophen, alcohol, ice packs and hot packs.  Action taken with second dose of mRNA-1273 in response to the events was unknown.  The outcome of events, soft tissue infection, knot under the skin below the elbow which has increased in size, elbow was huge and swollen, moved up towards the injection site, still having problems using his arm, area under his elbow was huge and swollen/moved towards injection site, and rendered elbow immobile were considered as not resolved.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

I woke at 6:30am on 04/07/2021 in a state of complete confusion and disorientation.  It was a level of disorientation I have never experienced before in my lifetime.  I fainted one time and was having extreme difficulty getting my bearings and walking and was simply in total "mental disarray".  I was having difficulty producing words, a prolonged stutter, you might say.  I was shaking.  The local paramedics came and I was taken to the local ER.  Because I was having difficulty speaking, the paramedics (and later the physicians) thought I might have had a TIA.  An MRI on 04/07/2021 at 5pm produced a negative result.  So i can only attribute my reaction to the vaccine.  It was very significant, and i thought it made sense to report it.
LAB_DATA: all bloodwork came back as normal.  as mentioned above, an MRI of my brain revealed a negative result.  There was concern about a possible TIA.
OTHER_MEDS: I take both Tadalafil 5mg daily and Loperamide (over the counter generic Immodium).

Right after the immunization she was fine, able to walk to the chair directly outside of pharmacy for observation. Approximately 5 minutes into observation, she waved healthcare worker down, healthcare worker immediately went to talk to her about her symptoms, healthcare worker grabbed an ice pack, while breaking the ice pack, patient fainted while she was sitting in the chair, healthcare worker held her head up to ensure proper breathing and spoke to patient, she came back after about 30 seconds, which is when healthcare worker assisted the patient in moving to the ground and putting her feet up. Healthcare worker or a pharmacy technician remained with the patient until her husband arrived. It took her husband approximately 25 minutes to get to the pharmacy, during that time healthcare worker did ask the patient if she wanted medical attention and she declined, knowing the feeling would subside. It did take her approximately 30 minutes to feel comfortable enough to sit up. Her husband took her out in a wheel chair.

Patient received vaccine around 3PM CST and proceeded to waiting area for the recommended waiting time. Within a few minutes of receiving the vaccination, around 3:05PM CST, patient complained of feeling dizzy. Patient was carefully laid down on the floor, given a pillow to protect his head, and feet were elevated. Patient was extremely sweaty and lightheaded/dizzy. Patient maintained consciousness and expressed that he was beginning to feel a bit better once he was lying down. He was provided a cold bottle of water if needed. Patient refused dispatching an ambulance, which I believed to be an acceptable option as he was already improving and never lost consciousness. A blood pressure cuff was obtained and his blood pressure was 138/94 pulse 69 at approximately 3:15PM EST. He did not know what his BP typically is, but I felt comfortable that he wouldn't likely pass out with this BP. He wanted to set up due to feeling better, so we cautiously helped him do so. After having him remain seated on the ground out of caution, he requested to stand up. He stated he was feeling much better and expressed at that point he wanted to leave. His girlfriend was with him and would be driving him home. It seemed that his symptoms had fully resolved by the time he left the waiting area and assured me he felt okay.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presented for her first COVID-19 vaccine. Approximately a minute after vaccine was given, she was noted to be seated upright in the passenger seat of her car, with head bent forward and eyes open. She was unresponsive, stiff posture, and was placed into a reclined position. She then had some posturing with head turned to the left, no eye deviation or nystagmus, no tonic-clonic movement. Radial pulse was thready, bradycardia was noted, with normal respirations. She was noted to become diaphoretic and pale/ashen color noted to the face and arms. She became responsive within a few minutes, however initially was not able to answer questions clearly. She had no loss of bowel or bladder function. EMS assisted with evaluation.  Initial blood pressure 78/31, HR 54, SpO2 100%.  EMS then transferred her to the stretcher and she was transitioned from her car to the ambulance. She continued to improve spontaneously with BP 94/61 then 103/60 and HR 86 then 74. SpO2 remained stable at 100%.  Skin color improved. She had normal responses to questions, no complaints of headache, dizziness, chest tightness, shortness of breath, numbness or tingling. She had some shaking/voluntary movement of the limbs and body noted, but she could control and stop this voluntarily, no myoclonic or tonic-clonic jerking noted.  After syncopal event occurred, mom reported that the patient has a history of syncope routinely with blood draws and vaccines in the past, however this episode was slightly more prolonged and seizure-like activity was different. She has had some jerking movement previously with syncope which lasts 20-30 seconds, different from today's response. No known history of seizure disorder.
LAB_DATA: 4 lead EKG obtained, unavailable to review.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At approximately 9:00 PM (roughly 11.5 hours after vaccination)  I became extremely light headed with slurred speech. I experienced tunnel vision and dizziness. My face turned white, and my lips were a blue color. I sat down immediately, which improved my condition temporarily.   But, within 2 minutes I began experiencing tunnel vision and dizziness again while sitting upright. I laid down on my back and elevated my legs.  My vision returned and but I remained dizzy and pale. I experienced some numbness and tingling in my extremities.  My wife attached a fingertip pulse oximeter to my finger at this time (we did not have a tool to check blood pressure on hand). My blood %SpO2 read between  95 and 98% and pulse ranged from 95 to 101 bpm.  I did NOT experience: difficulty breathing, swelling of the airway, nor itching.   Since I was not having difficulty breathing, and my symptoms seemed to indicate low blood pressure or potentially low blood sugar I decided to wait it out and see if my symptoms worsened.    While laying on the floor, I consumed a glass of milk and a few oreo cookies, hoping to counter hypoglycemia (if that's what was going on).  After approximately 15 minutes my condition began to improve - I could sit up slightly with only mild dizziness and color began returning to my face. After approximately 30 minutes, I was able to stand and walk to my couch and lay down. After around an hour, I was feeling almost back to normal with only a slight dizziness and tiredness remaining.  12 hours after the adverse event (24 hours post vaccination) I feel okay, slightly lightheaded but generally fine. I intend to call a doctor and discuss if any further tests are necessary.
LAB_DATA: My blood %SpO2 read between  95 and 98% and pulse ranged from 95 to 101 bpm via a fingertip pulse oximeter.
OTHER_MEDS: 1000 mg Acetaminophen approximately 6 hours after injection to counter mild fever (99 def F), body aches, and injection site soreness. Marijuana, approx 0.2 g, smoked, approximately 30 minutes prior to adverse event.

The MD gave me Oxycodone which helped some. The lymph node were no longer tender and sore by day the 28th or so.  The lesions/vesicles started to dry up by 04/02/21 but the  itching persisted and remained very painful. The back pain persisted throughout with difficulty sleeping due to the pain.  By the 4th of April, the lesions had dried completly and all the scabs had fallen off. Some of the nerve pain persisted but clothing was more bearable by this time.  As of today, there is some itching that remains and some back pain with some tenderness on my right torso.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 2/25/21 I received my first Moderna vaccine.  Later that day, I started to experience some brain fog and fatigue. this resolved itself after approximately 4 hours. On  3/3/21 I took my dose of Humira that I use for Crohn's Disease and about 3 hours later experienced extreme fatigue. I have been on Humira for 3.5 years and I have never experienced a reaction to the Humira like this. On 3/4/21, the next day after taking my Humira, I once again experienced extreme fatigue, a very bad headache and horrible brain fog to the point where the things I was reading on my computer and things people were saying to me was not making sense. I was also very nauseated and had severe diarrhea. I was tested for Covid just to be sure and I was negative. I went home and fell asleep and slept for 6 hours. I did feel better upon waking up.  Approximately one week later I experienced a sever migraine with visual disturbances.  On 3/15/21 I began having  a Crohn's flare. I had been in remission for 3.5 years with my last colonoscopy in October of 2019 showing  this and that my Crohn's ulcers had improved. I went to the ER on 3/16/21 in severe pain, was found to be in a flare with inflammation and swelling in my small intestine and a partial blockage. I was admitted to the hospital for 2 days where I received IV steroids and fluids. I was sent home on oral prednisone and now have to add additional medication to my Humira regimen for my Crohn's.  I am sure that some will say that none of this is related to the Moderna vaccine I received, but I have had no issues with my Crohn's in 3.5 years until I had this vaccine. All of my issues this past month coincide with receiving the vaccine and I have never had any side effects whatsoever from the Humira. In fact, it's always made me feel better when I've been due to take it, so I know that my symptoms are not from the Humira. I cannot say for sure if the vaccine caused my issues, however, it's pretty coincidental that I was feeling good and otherwise healthy until I had this vaccine.
PRIOR_VAX: flu vaccine, several years ago, not sure of the date, swelling and itching of my arm and shoulder where I had the vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received Covid vaccination/injection in right arm on 2/2/21. For the 1st four days, had occasional heart palpitations that lasted first 4 days then stopped--heart returned to normal with no more episodes. On 2/4/21, that night when I went to bed, I noticed a ringing in my left ear that became louder & louder as the next several days went by.  I then noticed substantial hearing loss in my left ear.  Also 2 days later, I started having a dull ache around my left ear along with the loud, high pitched ringing. I kept thinking it would get better but a week before my next vaccine, I called my ENT  who monitors a small lesion & hearing in my left middle ear.  I already had slight conductive hearing loss from this lesion and my last appointment/check up with her was in September 2020.  Dr. had me come to the hospital on 3/11/21 and a hearing test was performed and my left ear hearing had declined 15 decibels since my last hearing test in Sept 2020.  I was prescribed a Medrol Pak (steroids) for 1 week and returned on 3/23 for a 2nd hearing test with no improvement in my hearing or the loud ringing (tinnitus).  The Dr. told me that my hearing test showed damage to the left ear nerve.  I had also developed an inflamed, painful large sore under the left side of my tongue & was prescribed Triamcinolone Acetonide Dental Paste to use 2 x daily on the sore.  The Dr. ordered an MRI of my brain & left ear to make sure the lesion in my ear had not grown.  I had the MRI on 3/29/21 and returned to my Dr. on 3/30/21 for results. Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA.  On early morning of 04/02/2021 arm became very discolored (mostly bright red/scarlet color) between elbow and just below vaccination injection site.  Through the course of the weekend arm became worse but the initial pain changed to irritation/itching primarily.  On 04/05/2021 at 6 a.m. upon wakening arm was still vividly discolored but my blood pressure reading first thing was high (197/99 with a 90 pulse) which is very unusual for me now.  Not only that but I also experience at same time a nose bleed.  Since other than assuming in general that the arm discoloration connected somehow to the vaccination I had no idea if the spike in BP also connected and the nose bleed (since I rarely have any nose bleeds) I went to the ER - which is a small county hospitals about 3 miles from my home.  I did not attempt to take a Clonidine at home before going there as I wanted them to see if there was a connection between these 3 issues.  Upon arrival my blood pressure was taken again and it was the same high numbers as  at home not long before.  The ER doctor on duty that morning unfortunately didn't seem to  know what might be wrong with my arm and so she focused on bringing down my blood pressure by instructing a nurse to give me a Clonidine.  Within about a half hour when my BP had returned to normal they dismissed me to go home without any actual information as to whether the 3 issues were connected of not and without obviously having a clue as to what the situation was with my arm.   During the course of the day my daughter did some research on the internet and determined that it must be 'COVID Arm' that I was suffering from.  First thing the next morning (04/03/21) I called my GP doctor's office to try to get an appointment but unfortunately he was fully booked and so instead I called the the local Health Department and spoke with one of the nurses who works in their COVID Vaccination program.  On telling her of my experiences she confirmed that it sounded very much like COVID Arm.
LAB_DATA: None were run.  Only BP and pulse taken as described above.

The morning of April 3, staff at the Vaccination Clinic discovered a discrepancy in the preparation of Pfizer vaccine doses. It was discovered that several undiluted vaccine doses were administered. Staff accounted for all unused undiluted vaccine doses. Unfortunately, 10 undiluted vaccine doses had been administered to patients and were not able to be retrieved. This patient received one of the undiluted doses.   The medical team contacted the CDC to determine the potential side effects and observation requirements of receiving an undiluted vaccine. The CDC confirmed that the recipients of the undiluted doses may experience stronger side effects and symptoms than someone who received the diluted dose (sore arm, flu-like symptoms, etc.).  The site public health officer spoke with suspected recipients of the undiluted vaccine to explain potential medical side effects.  follow up to monitor their status.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The morning of April 3, staff at the Vaccination Clinic discovered a discrepancy in the preparation of Pfizer vaccine doses. It was discovered that several undiluted vaccine doses were administered. Staff accounted for all unused undiluted vaccine doses. Unfortunately, 10 undiluted vaccine doses had been administered to patients and were not able to be retrieved. This patient received one of the undiluted doses.   The medical team contacted the CDC to determine the potential side effects and observation requirements of receiving an undiluted vaccine. The CDC confirmed that the recipients of the undiluted doses may experience stronger side effects and symptoms than someone who received the diluted dose (sore arm, flu-like symptoms, etc.).  The site public health officer spoke with suspected recipients of the undiluted vaccine to explain potential medical side effects. The  will follow up to monitor their status.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had no major reactions to first vaccine- some soreness around injection site and slight fatigue, but nothing major.  I had the 2nd vaccine on Saturday, March 27.  Until Wednesday I was fine- same side effects as the first injection.  Wednesday and Thursday I became extremely fatigued.  On Friday morning I woke up covered in hives.  It was no better Saturday, so I had a telehealth appointment and was told it was likely a delated allergic reaction to the vaccne.  I was given 40 mg of prednisone to take daily for 5 days and 10 mg of zyrtec once a day for 10 days.  Symptoms improved slightly, but not nearly like they should have.  Yesterday I have another big flare up and since my last dose of prednisone was today, I went in to a different Urgent Care and was given a Celestone shot.  I woke up at 4:00 a.m. this morning with my hives being worse than they have been the entire time.  I took my meds and benedryl, used ice packs, and fell back asleep.  When I got up, the hives were back to how they  have been the past few days- no better, but no worse either.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I felt fine immediately after the injection - just a little pain in the arm where I got the injection and when raising my arm. By 6:30 pm I was achy all over and my legs were aching a lot. When I went to bed around 8:00, I hurt all over (achy and flu-like feeling, but no fever). I dozed off and on and about midnight when I woke up, I had a very rapid heartbeat. This went on all night and into the morning. It was hard to get any sleep at all. When I'd get up to go to the bathroom, I was slightly dizzy and unsteady on my feet. After I got up at 6:30 am, the highest my heartrate got was 113, then it finally began going down. I was still hurting all over, felt extremely tired, and now had fever - 99.8. The fever lasted off and on all day and into the next night. I was also very nauseated all day and I felt extremely bloated. I also had a bad headache. When I woke up on Friday, my fever and the headache was gone, but I felt extremely tired and weak and still nauseated. I slept most of the day and I still ached all over, but not as much. My lymph nodes were also swollen. On Friday afternoon, I walked up to the mailbox and I was winded and unsteady. On Saturday, I felt a little better, but was still extremely tired. By Saturday night, all the aches, pains and headache were back and I didn't sleep well at all. I rested most of Sunday and felt a little better Sunday evening. The aches and pains were going away, but I was still very tired and exhausted. I felt the same way when I woke up on Monday morning. It seemed like the vaccination made the aches and pains I normally had with Fibromyalgia about three times as bad as usual. And I was still very bloated feeling all over. By Monday afternoon the nausea finally went away. By Monday afternoon I was feeling a little better, but still tired. On Tuesday I felt better still and I noticed that I wasn't bloated as much. It seemed like I was getting back to normal.
OTHER_MEDS: 6:00 am Doxycycline and Aspirin Noon - Balziva (generic for Ovcon-35), Centrum Women's Vitamin
ALLERGIES: Penicillin, Compozine, Sulfa Drugs, Vancomycin, and a long list of other medications. Also allergic to bees.

Patient was observed for 30 min after her second dose of covid-19 vaccine (note patient decided to take diphenhydramine immediately after receiving this dose of vaccine because she experienced a spike in her blood pressure with her first covid-19 vaccine). Patient felt fine and left the vaccine clinic. But about 2 hours after receiving the second dose, patient developed numbness, right upper and lower extremity weakness and headache. Upon presentation to the ED, patient developed right sided facial droop and ongoing right upper and lower extremity weakness and headache. Stroke protocols were initiated including offering tPA for clinical stroke, but patient declined it.   At workup, her EKG showed a sinus rhythm, she had not reported recent illness.  A CT angiogram showed no significant flow limiting stenosis either in the neck or head and there was no perfusion deficit.  However, incidental bilateral aneurysms were discovered at the anterior cerebral arteries at the junction of the A3 segments and pericallosal arteries.  There was no evidence that they had hemorrhage and they are small, less than 5 mm in diameter and neurosurgery has evaluated the patient and is not recommending any urgent intervention.   The next day the patient was doing well, presenting symptoms/deficits resolved except for ongoing mild headache. An MRI examination of the brain has shown no acute infarct and normal brain morphology was described.  She had an echocardiogram, which showed grossly normal left ventricular size and systolic function with an estimated ejection fraction of 65%.  Amlodipine was started for elevated blood pressure. Note: patient had a history of hypertension but was not on medications for this prior to admission.   Neurology consult = ?This is a peculiar event.  It is unclear if the patient had a TIA or COVID reaction to a COVID vaccination or a reaction to headache.  She does not exhibit a completed stroke on MRI scan.  She has recovered completely except for mild headache.  Incidental aneurysms were discovered and at some point she should have follow up for that. She should have a follow up with the stroke service.  In the meantime, I think it is reasonable to continue with daily aspirin on this patient.  Note that she had a cryptogenic TIA.?

She got her vaccine and after she received it she was okay, after 10 minutes she had a heated sensation to her neck, and chest and radiated down her right arm to her finger.  Her legs from the knees down went numb.  She had waves of this that would come and go.  Then her upper lip got numb decided to leave as feeling it may have been anxiety.  On her way home in the car she had these reactions again and called her husband and told him that something was not right and that she felt weird.  She talked herself out of going to the ER, and went home.  She still was feeling really weird to be ok that came and went.  She called her friend who is a nurse who told her to take Ibuprofen and to go to bed.  She felt better after about 2 hours, and seemed to be doing okay periodically until the day before yesterday when she started feeling numbness in her legs, arms and then her upper lip which was pretty severe.   The heat from the arm is burning and burns to her upper chest and neck.  Yesterday morning she could hardly feel her feet saw a report of somebody getting Guillain Barre from it.  She took an Aleeve PM to go to sleep.  She woke up yesterday morning and the muscle pain was go but the numbness was still there.   She called the CDC who told her to contact us and to get in touch with her PCP and she was seen by her yesterday who ruled out Guillain Barre.  She examined her and said that her that the glands are swollen and relays the reaction to the injection and that may be causing the neurological numbness in her arms and legs.  She put her on a 5 day steroid to see if that helps to alleviate her symptoms.   She does feel better today but still having some numbness in the arms and legs, and swelling in her glands.
OTHER_MEDS: Multivitamin, zinc,  calcium, vitamin C, Turmeric.
PRIOR_VAX: 1st vaccine, had the same symptoms other than the lymph node reaction.  Soreness in her arm and very tired.

The morning of April 3, staff at the Community Vaccination Clinic discovered a discrepancy in the preparation of Pfizer vaccine doses. It was discovered that several undiluted vaccine doses were administered. Staff accounted for all unused undiluted vaccine doses. Unfortunately, 10 undiluted vaccine doses had been administered to patients and were not able to be retrieved. This patient received one of the undiluted doses.   The medical team contacted the CDC to determine the potential side effects and observation requirements of receiving an undiluted vaccine. The CDC confirmed that the recipients of the undiluted doses may experience stronger side effects and symptoms than someone who received the diluted dose (sore arm, flu-like symptoms, etc.).  The site public health officer spoke with suspected recipients of the undiluted vaccine to explain potential medical side effects. The Health District will follow up to monitor their status.

I had begun taking the Escitalopram at the end of January. my dose was increased from 5 mg per day to 10 mg per day on the day following my covid vaccine on the 26th. At 10:15 A.M, pt received Moderna Covid Vaccine, 1st dose. At 10:17, RN and APN were called over by worker and observer, in which worker was holding pt on the ground. When RN and APN arrived, pt was unresponsive for about a 1 second, then awakened. Pt got up on her own and was sat on a wheelchair. Pt was taken back to triage area. Pt told us her full name and DOB. At 10:20, vitals were taken, BP was 87/65, pulse was 57, O2 was 98. Pt was alert and oriented x4. Pt was accompanied by sister. Per pt, she has a history of this happening mostly every time she gets a shot. Pt reports being scared of needles, and this happening often. Per pt, she has no history of cormobidity, no history of allergies. RN offered pt to call an ambulance, in which pt declined. Per pt, this happens often when receiving a vaccine, as well as when she got one of her tattoos. Pt was given glucose water as well as a water bottle. BP was taken again at 10:25, pt BP 106/68, P: 70, O2 @ 98. Pt color beginning to return to normal, pt reports feeling better. Pt states she did not eat any breakfast this morning. RN spoke to observer. Per observer, he saw pt start to get pale, in which he grabbed pt, and assisted her to the ground. Pt did not hit head. Vitals were taken again at 10:35, BP @ 98/70, P: 85, O2 @ 99. SIster stated she is driving, and will not let pt drive, agreed with sister. Appointment scheduled for tomorrow for f/u with a provider. BP taken @ 10:55, BP was 100/ 64, P: 80, O2 was 99. Pt is alert and oriented x4. Pt was again offered an ambulance or to be driven to the ER, pt declined. Pt given strict instructions on when to go to ED, pt and sister agreed. Per pt, she has work today @ 2pm, RN advised pt to stay home and rest, pt agreed. RN will send letter to pt to excuse her from work. Due to pt BP being WNL, pt being alert and oriented, pt was wheeled out in the wheelchair by RN with sister. No further questions or concerns.
PRIOR_VAX: Unknown due to pt not remembering. Pt reported this happening often when receiving any vaccine due to pt being scared of needles

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Starting approximately one week after the first dose of the Moderna vaccine, I started developing gastrointestinal symptoms. Over the course of the past two months, I have not been able to eat a normal diet and have needed to restrict to plain carbohydrates, some meats, and cooked vegetables. I have experienced frequent diarrhea (at least once a day), though the likelihood decreases if I stick to a plain diet. This has lasted for over two months.  My provider is considering diagnosing me with Irritable Bowel Syndrome. I have not had such symptoms prior to the week following my first vaccination dose; these appeared suddenly and have not remitted since. These symptoms are accompanied by fatigue, loss of appetite, and unintended weight loss. These are causing me significant impairment.  Note that I also experienced a vasovagal episode when I received my first dose of the vaccine, though recovered within the day.   To test the possibility that these symptoms are the result of anxiety given my history, I have increased my antidepressant medication dosage. When my GI symptoms suddenly started in early February, I did have a concurrent increase in anxiety/panic. However, my psychological symptoms have since then remitted, but my GI symptoms never did. I also have never experienced the level of GI problems, as well as specific dietary restrictions, due only to anxiety in my lifetime.
LAB_DATA: Blood panel (no anemia or other problems noted) Physical exam (normal)
HISTORY: history of anxiety and panic disorder in remission history of major depressive disorder in remission

First dose: Dec 16 Symptoms spanning 36 hours after injection as well as occasional joint pain in left elbow, wrist and knuckles. 36hr symptoms included: Fever, fatigue, muscle and joint pain in legs and arms, chills. 2nd dose, jan 6: Symptoms spanning ~60 hours (two days following vaccination + day of vaccination)Symptoms included: headache, low grade fever, muscle and joint pain in legs and both arms, chills. Symptoms almost completely resolved after that period, occasionally had some very mild joint pain still.*Note after both doses, pain in left arm was more severe than right arm* Starting the night of Jan 22 (fri) started having light leg pain, which carried into the 22nd. Dismissed it as too much walking the next day.Jan 24: leg pain a bit more severe, from a 1-2 to a 2-3. Included joint pain in left knee and ankle. Jan 25: pain in both legs at a 3-4, also mild pain in left arm (1-2) as well as joint pain. Jan 26: pain in left arm more severe, leg pain similar in severe. Very mild pain in right arm starting that evening, though only in upper arm. No joint pain in right arm Jan 27: pain in left arm similar in severity, slight increase in right arm pain, would rate 2-3 in right arm, 3-4 in left arm, 3-4 in legs. Muscle weakness in legs (legs shaking when walking down stairs for example) Jan 28 (Thurs):Symptoms started fading. Arm pain lowered in severity in both arms, as did leg pain. By Saturday all that remained was mild leg pain (1-2 in severity)Since then, leg pain has persisted.  Week of Feb 14, leg pain increased in severity back to a 3-4. Visited the doctor on the 17th and had blood-work done on the 23rd after severity didn't decrease. Blood-work was normal other than slightly elevated lymphocyte % (50.8%)Visited a specialty medicine doctor on 2/25 and had x-rays done of legs. Results normal. Thought to have developed Achilles tendinitis. Possibly attributed to inflammation in legs, doctor wasn't sure. Rough quote "could it be from the vaccine, possibly, we just don't know." Have been doing stretches since which has helped the leg pain. Starting on March 12, I began to have pain in my left arm again, and ended up getting vertigo that evening. The arm pain persisted on and off from then on out, as well as occasional dizziness, which I treated with Dramamine. I did get an appointment scheduled with a neurologist in May that I still have. On March 25, I began to feel unwell, with a fever, dizziness, and a headache. That worsened into the evening, and I woke up at around 3 am with a high fever, that ended up going to about 103 F, and began vomiting around 4:30am on Friday, which persisted into the evening. On Saturday evening I began to feel better. With that recovery, the constant leg pain and frequent arm pain seemed to be gone, and has yet to return to the degree that it had been prior to that bout of sickness.  I do still occasionally get arm or leg pain, but it's minor and only lasts about 20-30 minutes at a time.

Patient received the vaccine. Immunizing tech stated: the patient seemed fine at the time of the shot. After administration of the shot the patient began to bleed out of injection site (like normal). The immunizing tech swabbed the area with cotton and placed a Band-Aid on the patient then stepped back into the pharmacy to grab another band aid while the patient remained at the immunization chair. The tech applied another band aid and told the patient to wait 15 minutes after the immunization and directed him to a waiting chair. The tech came back into the pharmacy and was cleaning the immunization basket when the patient's wife yelled for help. At this point I went out to the patient. Another tech called 911, another grabbed a nearby EpiPen. The immunizing tech grabbed the e-kit while I was out with the patient while he was unresponsive. Patient was unresponsive and slouched in chair. His wife and I supported the neck of the patient and laid him on the floor. I checked pulse and breathing to which both were present. Patient was still unresponsive and making strange movements. Pulse and breathing remained present and then the patient became responsive relatively quickly. At this point patient responsive and answering questions and moving fine. He asked if he had passed out then stated, he had a phobia of needles and said he felt nauseated. (wife previously stated he had a fear of injections). Soon after the ambulance showed up and I told the paramedics the above story. After a few more minutes I checked in with the paramedics and they said the patient was doing fine. Lastly, he was taken out of store with paramedics.

PharmD ran to patient and observed him lying facedown with head facing left. Eyes open but unresponsive, his name was called with no response. Right as he was observed to be breathing normally with a steady pulse, patient had mild seizure with jerking movements. He was turned to his side during seizure event lasting no longer that 2 minutes. Patient then regained consciousness and was kept on his side. Was alert and oriented. He knew where he was, who he was, what day it was. He was able to answer all 911 dispatcher questions relayed to him. Dispatcher advised he could sit up on floor, which he did. PharmD stayed right behind him until paramedics arrived. He was kept talking to stay alert. It was unknown if he hit his head on the initial fall. Paramedics arrived and checked BP/Pulse/EKG. As I was walking I would just start falling over and I'd have to put my hand out to catch me so I didn't fall to the ground. By Sunday morning it was mostly resolved, though I did have some occasional incidents that day (Sunday) and the next (Monday). For example I would be doing exercise at home (working out to a fitness game), and when moving my hands and feet all of a sudden I would start tipping over. If I planted my feet and just moved my hands I was okay. It is now Wednesday morning and I haven't had any balance issues since Monday night. Note that I didn't really feel dizzy, I just unexpectedly started falling over when this happened.

In observation area, my tongue swelled up - nurse held be back for a bit to observe and gave me bottled water.  The injection site arm went dead and unable to move (left arm stated on my vaccination card but it was the RIGHT arm that was jabbed. Another inconsistency of this whole process).  I had weird tingliness shooting up to my neck/back of neck. After finally being released from the observation area when the tongue swelling went down, I was tired walking to my car.  That night I was exhausted and couldn't get off the couch and nauseated. The nausea and fatigue hit in waves over the next day.  On Monday (second morning after the shot), I could not get out of bed.  After finally getting up, I went to work. At work I was still dealing with fatigued, shortness of breath, my head was dizzy and light, then mid-morning I had sharp stabbing chest pains under my left breast, the pain shot up to my left neck and jaw. I could not breathe. The more I tried to breathe, the sharper my chest pains became. I had emailed my primary care doctor twice that morning because of symptoms and never heard back so when the chest pains hit, I went to the ER. At the ER they ran EKG, blood work, XRays. Kept me all day. At the end, they told me  I was healthy and let me go. The doctor had ZERO regard or interest in the fact that all of this started after the vaccine. No where in my notes was it noted that I had the vaccine.  The nurses told me this was a trend with the patients coming into ER complaining of post-vaccine symptoms and not having them documented.  I had breathing issues for almost two weeks after the vaccine where I would be short of breath and winded, not able to complete sentences without stopping for air.  I still have awkward breathing moments.  I called healthcare facility nightly to report this and again was told to just monitor my symptoms. I feel like this whole process has been an isolating, careless time where my vaccine side effects have NOT been taken seriously.
LAB_DATA: ER visit - EKG, X-Rays, multiple blood tests.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Shortly following the initial vaccine, I felt slightly queasy and my arm had a stinging sensation radiating from the injection site.  The next day I had a headache that lasted for several days, and my arm was extremely painful (for several weeks.)  Following the second vaccine I also felt particularly queasy (stomach unease) and a headache.  In about 24 hours post second dose I felt extremely ill.  I had severe chills, fever, and loss of appetite.  I could not control my body temperature and my body ached all over.  The following morning I felt well enough to go to work but exhausted, headache and muscle aches.  My arm was painful for a few weeks. I have never experienced a vaccine reaction such as this with any previous vaccines in the past. It has been about 2 month since my last covid-19 vaccine. Since then I have felt sluggish, foggy and "just not myself."  I feel like I just cannot recharge my "battery" completely.  Simple tasks take much longer to complete and I have difficulty with short term memory or thinking of the names of items I use on a daily basis or names of people I see regularly.  This has given me a great deal of anxiety because I do not completely trust myself to do my job appropriately without second guessing myself or having someone else check my work. I intend to follow up with my physician about this but as of yet have not consulted with anyone.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Two days after receiving my shot, I began to experience mild dizziness. Four days after my vaccine, the dizziness began to intensify to the point where on day 5 (Sunday), I could not get out of bed.  I attempted to go to an urgent care facility, but none where open.  I called my PCP and talked to the covering doctor.  I was told that it might be BPPV and was given a prescription for meclazine.  On  day 6, I was a little better and tried to make an appointment with my PCP (I was unable to get one until this coming Friday), so I went to an urgent care.  They seemed to agree with the BPPV diagnosis and told me to look on T.V. for how to do the Epley maneuver.  It has now been 8 days since my vaccine and I am still experiencing dizziness, but am able to function with some limits (I haven't driven my car as of yet).  The Epley maneuver did not seem to help.  Besides the dizziness, my ears feel full and especially in the morning, I have a bit of a problem with my eyes focusing correctly.
LAB_DATA: On 4/5/21, when I went to the urgent care facility, they just performed some visual tests (ie,. walking on my toes/heels, touching my nose with my finger/eyes closed, following the movement of their finger with my eyes).
OTHER_MEDS: multi-vitamin, vitamin D3, Zyflamend, CBD oil, Lorazepam
ALLERGIES: Benadryl, raw almonds, kiwi, cherries, plums, multiple seasonal/animal allergies

51-year-old female presents to ED with left lower extremity edema.  Patient reports left lower extremity swelling, particularly in the calf and ankle couple weeks ago.  She denies any specific traumas or injuries, states she initially thought maybe she had sprained her ankle but is noted that the swelling had not improved.  Says theres some slight pain but moreso the swelling that was concerning to her. Has not noticed any erythema or ecchymosis.  No numbness, tingling, paresthesias.  No fevers or chills.  No chest pain or shortness of breath.  She is currently on estrogen oral contraceptive, no recent travel, immobilization, medical procedure, surgery, or trauma, hemoptysis, malignancy, coagulation disorders, history of DVT or PE.  States initially followed up outpatient and had an ultrasound that was done and she was instructed to come to ED for positive result.  No further symptoms or complaints at this time.  The patient's symptoms, exam, workup, and disposition were discussed with ED attending Doctor, proceeded with management accordingly. Physical exam as above. Patient afebrile, hemodynamically stable, well-appearing.  Chart review from earlier today shows ultrasound positive study for subacute nonocclusive proximal DVT in the left popliteal vein, and subacute superficial thrombophlebitis in the left lesser saphenous vein. No evidence of cellulitis or infection at this time there's no warmth or erythema or streaking. No bilateral edema, JVD, or evidence of fluid overload. Suspect patient's symptoms of left lower extremity swelling and pain likely secondary to the DVT and thrombophlebitis. No bony TTP or injuries no indication for bony imaging. No cp, sob, tachycardia, hypoxia.  Do not suspect PE. She does have a leukocytosis no urinary or respiratory symptoms lower suspicion UTI or pneumonia. No neck stiffness or pain to suggest meningitis. Area doesn't appear cellulitic at this time but could possibly be due to early cellulitis and the superficial thrombophlebitis. She's afebrile non septic appearing and will be started on abx nonetheless and she is given strict return precautions regarding this.  She has no contraindications to anticoagulation including no thrombocytopenia, active hemorrhage, history intracerebral hemorrhage, chronic anticoagulation. No findings suggestive of phlegmasia cerulea dolens. Labs including kidney function, liver enzymes discussed with ED pharmacist matt nagar. Patient has no significant commodities and is an appropriate candidate for outpatient DVT treatment with eliquis. She is educated regarding eliquis by ED pharmacist.  Discussed with patient the need to contact her doctor tomorrow regarding the oral contraceptives that she is currently taking, as there may likely need to be a change and/or discontinuation of this secondary to patient's DVT and starting on Eliquis.  She is instructed not to make any changes to medication regimen until she contacted her PCP, and again reiterated that she needs to speak with them first thing tomorrow morning regarding her birth control.  Patient expresses understanding. Given overall presentation and ED workup, believe patient is stable for discharge home at this time. Discussed at length strict written and verbal ED return precautions with patient. Patient will follow up with PCP, will start on eliquis and clinda. Patient expressed understanding and agreeable to this plan for discharge and follow up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About a week after the first Covid shot, I started to get a chickenpox like rash that started on my thighs and progressed down my legs, then to my arms, neck and stomach.  The rash caused an intense itching.  After the second covid shot, the rash became even more intense.  I tried over-the-counter itch relieving medicines to no avail.  Finally I went to the doctor and she prescirbed Methylprednisolone for 6 days.  This seemed to help, but even after the 6 days of treatment the rash is slightly visible and itching can flare up still.   I wasn't sure what had caused the rash as I had done nothing different and it was only my suspicion that it might have been as a result of the Covid vaccination, as I hadn't seen any publicity about a delayed onset of an all body rash  as a side effect of the vaccine.  Today it was in the news, and that confirmed my opinion that I had been having an adverse side effect of the vaccine.
LAB_DATA: Only the doctor's visual observation of the rash resulted in the prescription of Methylprednisolone.  At the time we weren't aware that it was being caused by the Covid vaccinations and when I suggested it as a possibility, she acknowledged that it could be, but that not enough was known yet about the long term effects of the vaccine to confirm that possibility.
OTHER_MEDS: Arazo Nutrition: Joint Support (Glucosamine, Chondroitin, MSM) Nature's Trove:  SAMe (I stopped taking any of these after the rash appeared.  The rash persisted)
ALLERGIES: Epinephrine (as administered at dentist office.  It makes my heart race.)

Patient had acute onset left sided numbness at 12:30pm while she was under her 15min observation post-covid19 vaccine injection. The patient reported that the numbness initially started in her left cheek that spread to the left side of her head then down her left side of the body reaching her toes. Patient was evaluated for stroke and according to the treating physician, the neuro exam was normal and patient answered appropriately for feeling touch or degree of touch equally bilaterally. NIHSS was 0 and MRI showed no acute CVA. The blood sugar was in the 50s with EMS. According to the treating physician, the symptoms may be related to the hypoglycemia at the same time as the incident. The physician also reports that the patient was very anxious in general and at times stated she had numbness that was worsening but at other times was witnessed walking around the room and to the bathroom by nursing staff without need for assistance or deficits. The patient was kept for observation and discharged the day after admission. A reaction to the vaccine cannot be completely ruled out considering the onset of symptoms but there may be other causes. The patient was asked to report this to the vaccination site prior to receiving the 2nd dose and be cleared by her PCP for the 2nd dose. This report is being entered in a abundance of caution in the setting of this new vaccine.
LAB_DATA: BS 50s in EMS; MRI and neuro exam negative for stroke
CUR_ILL: Hypoglycemia in route to hospital  Blood sugar in the 50s

I was about 4.5 weeks pregnant with the first dose of the vaccine; and 7.5 weeks with the second dose.  After the first dose, my hcg beta hormone level wasn't rising as fast as it should (ie. it wasn't doubling to tripling every 2 days) so I had to continue to get blood drawn to monitor it.  Then it had one big rise after 1.5 weeks; but soon after, I started spotting lightly daily.  After about a week of daily light spotting, I started heavily bleeding (like a menstrual period) on 3/25 (one day before my second dose).  I went for a sonogram and it was confirmed that the fetus had no heartbeat. We waited a few days after the second does to redo the sonogram but the bleeding had continued and the second sonogram showed no fetus-- meaning I had a miscarriage where the fetus was naturally eliminated through the bleeding.  I am being followed on a weekly basis for blood draws by my obgyn office to ensure that my hcg hormone level falls to 0.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 9 hours after receiving the Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine EUA, I experienced sudden fatigue followed by onset of severe muscle and joint pain including severe head pain followed by severe chills followed by fever and excessive sweating. I was very dizzy and felt disoriented. I was in bed when all this happened and was already wearing warm clothes under the covers. The muscle and joint pain was so severe, I couldn't grip anything including my cell phone (my wrists were in sharp pain). The head pain was so severe I was sensitive to light regardless of how dim it was. I felt like my toes were curled, but that could have been me "bracing" and tightening up due to the total body pain. I could move very little. It was very strange. These symptoms persisted through the night. The following morning at around 9am, I still had a very bad headache that made me nauseated and continued to be sensitive to light. Some of the joint and muscle pain tapered down enough for me to get out of bed to go potty but it was exhausting to walk 5 feet to the bathroom and then get back in bed. I still ran a mild fever. At around 1pm I took a Tylenol that helped subside the symptoms but felt wiped out all day. By the following day (Monday), I was feeling better getting more energy and by that Monday evening, I felt like nothing ever happened. I'm sure these just fall into perhaps the more severe level of the side effects, but I was frightened by the intense sharp muscle and joint pain to the point I couldn't even grip anything.
LAB_DATA: None. Had consult over the phone with a nurse the morning after the side effects.
OTHER_MEDS: multi vitamin, extra vitamin D, extra vitamin C, extra zinc, Omega - 3s, protein shakes; no medication of any kind was taken at time of vaccination
HISTORY: mild asthma, high cholesterol, hydradenitis suppurativa

Prior to the first vaccination, I was accustomed to walking 1 to 2 miles almost every day with no difficulty at all.   The initial reaction to the second dose was less than with the first.  (I didn't walk for two days after that one.)  However, it worsened over the next couple of weeks so that again I could barely walk 1/4 mile without making things worse again.  Now it's about 3 1/2 weeks since dose #2 and it does seem to be starting to improve, but slowly.  (And I took ibuprofen for 5 days last week, 400 mg 2x/day, which helped.)   The only other reaction I had to either dose was the usual sore arm.  Neither affected the L hip which still has severe arthritis.   I have kept a day-by-day journal with details.

Patient remained in chair throughout seizure and was physically stabilized by EMT . His seizure lasted approximately 1 minute. At 11:38 am, patient was non-verbal, but breathing at a rate of 20 res/min. Patient nodded to respond to neurological assessment.  Vital signs were taken every 5 minutes. At 11:38 am, BP 150/77 sitting, HR 103, SpO2 97% RA, RR 20 res/min labored. Patient was transferred to anti-gravity chair with assistance from EMTs. At 11:39 am, patient was able to verbally respond to questions. Patient was alert and oriented to person, place, time and situation. Patient states "I just had a seizure". At 11:42 am, BP 152/98, HR 104,  Spo2 at 95%, RR 22 res/min, labored, patient stated "I feel palpitation". Staff approached patient calmly, encouraged deep breathing, provided quiet environment. Upon assessment, patient was alert, oriented X4, clear speech, communicated in Spanish and English. At 11:45 EMS arrived. patient stated "I feel a lot better". Patient was transferred into a gurney and transported to hospital. Emergency responders left with patient at 11:57 am. Patient was accompanied by his brother .

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Upon receiving the injection I was dizzy and a nurse brought me water. When I returned to my workplace, I got a migraine and felt mentally cloudy. The following day, I could barely lift my left arm and had some muscle soreness.  I was very fatigued for several days. Then, about a week after receiving the vaccine, I had severe muscle spasms in my back. They began in the thoracic region but at times the pain would travel to my lower back as well. These spasms continued for over a week. I sought relief by having a 60-minute massage, and the massage therapist informed me that she felt inflammation along the length of my spine, not in one localized area as with an injury, but along the erectors of my spine. The massage did help, but I still have chronic back pain, and have had migraines about once a week. I obtained a medical marijuana card and I now take CBD daily and use THC oral spray when I have a migraine or more severe back pain. I consulted with a neurologist who promptly dismissed my symptoms and said that it couldn't be from the vaccine, but there is absolutely nothing else that could have caused this. I am otherwise healthy and have had no injuries or events occur except for this vaccine.
LAB_DATA: I no longer trust medical doctors, no thank you.

1 minute after vaccine injection I experienced a tightening of my throat.  It was very uncomfortable and made it difficult to swallow  and felt like a "lump in my throat".  I asked an onsite nurse if this was a common reaction, and she offered medical attention.  I denied it because it was not getting worse.  She gave me a bottle of water and it seemed to help it a bit while drinking.  But, quickly returned after water was swallowed.  I was monitored for 30 minutes as recommended.  The tightness remained for 1 hour post vaccine injection and disappeared as quickly as it started.  I fear the second dose may be worse.

The next day I had the normal symptoms that I had expected. I worked through the next two days with headaches. On the fifth day I had a sudden onset of severe abdominal pain and a migraine like headache followed by the chills. These symptoms repeated two to four times daily for four days. I also had low grade abdominal cramping which is ongoing. I am unsure whether this is contractions or abdominal problems. I communicated with my Obstetrician and my GI doctor. My water broke at 21 weeks, but I did not lose the baby. I am currently 22 weeks pregnant and on bed rest.  I was hospitalized for four days. On Monday the 29th I had a CRP of 85 and by Friday April 2nd it dropped to 35. On Monday my WBC was 14.1. I am unsure of the outcome right now.

Had vaccine at 2:15 in the afternoon on 4/1/2021. That night in bed had mild itching on tops of both legs, thought it was dry skin.  Next morning I noticed red splotches on both legs from top of thigh to just below knee, front and sides (not on back of legs). That night about 10:30 I woke up with severe itching and hives on the same areas of both legs.  Bumps and red splotches and very hot.  Called Hospital and told me to take a Benadryl and go to ER if I experienced swelling of tongue or difficulty breathing.  I had neither.  I only had Cetirizine Hydrochloride 10 mg so I took one of those. Itching went away in about 1/2 hour.  Got Benadryl next day and Cortisone cream.  Red splotches are lessening each day but definitely still there.  It doesn't itch during the day only at night. So I am still taking the Benadryl before bed.  I had no other side effects besides the hives.  No fever, no headache, no body ache, no pain at injection side, no chills.  The vaccine did sting when going in and lasted a few minutes after.  I had no other changes that might cause this. Didn't work outside, clothes the same, eating the same, nothing different that would trigger this.

Approximately 6 hours after the vaccination, I experienced a severe tinnitus, or ringing in the left ear. While the intensity has settled down somewhat, I now have a constant, unremitting ringing  in my left ear that is loud enough to be bothersome most of the day. It is still many times louder than anything I have experienced before. I had no other noise exposure or out-of-the-ordinary events that might trigger this.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within a few days of the vaccination, I developed extreme flatulence, with frequent and copious discharges of exceedingly foul-smelling gas throughout the day, sometimes as often as four or more times within an hour. My digestion seemed sluggish and irregular, and I experienced a sense of being bloated (which the discharges somewhat relieved).   All these symptoms continued for about three weeks. At first I thought they simply had to do with something I might have eaten, but this seemed not to be the case. Throughout, my diet, dietary supplements, residence, sleep, environment, and daily routine remained the same -- and the same as they had been for months before.  Additional information for Item 18: Finally, about two weeks ago, I began taking an Ayurvedic digestive medicine (Dashamularista), once daily after lunch, which helped greatly. The discharges of gas reduced considerably in frequency and copiousness and were no longer abnormally foul-smelling. As of this day, however, flatulence still seems somewhat more than usual. Of course, I cannot unerringly testify to a cause-and-effect relationship between the vaccination and the symptoms I have described. But I see no other likely candidate for a cause.   I should mention that within the last few days I have developed mild but disturbing inflammation in the joints of both hands, particularly the knuckles. I have not had this before. I have also felt somewhat listless. (This, however, is not a symptom new for me.) in the last few days I have also developed a mild edema in both feet. But I have had this before from time to time, and the present instance might be attributable to variables such as a change in weather. (In the past this edema was diagnosed as lymphatic in origin, not circulatory.)
OTHER_MEDS: Every two months: Neurobion Forte IM. Additional information for Item 9: Daily: Folic acid (400 mcg), Vitamin C (1000 mg), Vitamin D3 (15 mcg), Silymarin (150 mg).

At urgent care, she was hypoxic with Sat 82%, therefore she was transferred to ED for further w/u. Lab w/u showed BNP of 1,074 and trop of 32. She was found to have a negative POC COVID-19 and PCR is pending. Bil venous Dopplers show acute occlusive DVT in the R popliteal vein above and below the knee w/ slow flow in the R fem vein and no DV IN the LLE. TTE on 03/31/2021 showed EF 65-70% w/ G2DD, mod-severe RV failure and severe pulmonary HTN, mod TR, and dilated IVC. Decision was made to CT chest w/ contrast despite renal function given high suspicion for PE. CT chest w/ contrast showed large clot burden PE w/ findings c/w R heart strain, a 12x9 mm lobulated nodule in the RUL concerning for neoplasm, increasing patchy infiltrates, and increasing R pleural effusion and new trace L pleural effusion. Patient required 12L O2 via NC. IR was contacted at but felt that patient was not a candidate for CDT or for IVC filter. Patient was transferred to ICU for further care. Patient received IV heparin per the PE Protocol from, Alteplase 40mg on 4/1, and was started on treatment dose of Eliquis.
LAB_DATA: (3/31/21) CT Thorax w/ contrast: Large amount of pulmonary embolism with findings concerning for right heart strain. Consider interventional radiology consultation. Changes of pulmonary arterial hypertension.12 x 9 mm lobulated nodule in the right upper lobe could represent neoplasm. Recommend PET scan or consider tissue diagnosis.Mild patchy infiltrate in the upper lobes with interval increase. This may be infectious or inflammatory however some of this could be related to pulmonary infarction.Increased small right pleural effusion and new trace left pleural effusion.  (3/31/21)  Venous Doppler Bilateral: Acute, occlusive DVT in the right popliteal vein above and below the knee.*  Slow flow in the distal right femoral vein. *  No DVT in the left lower extremity.
