Five minutes after receiving her 1st COVID vaccine, patient began complaining about  itchiness and swelling of her tongue, along with chest tightness and shortness of breath. Patient also begin feeling lightheaded.  Patient was assessed and was found to  be breathing, but her pulse was weak and thready.  A blood pressure cuff was applied to patient right arm, but the monitor was unable to generate a specific blood pressure number. Patient was administered 0.3 mg of epinephrine intramuscularly in her right thigh. She was also given 10 ml (25 mg) of diphenhydramine.  Patient was moved from the sitting to the supine position.  Patient's subjective dyspnea improved, and her airway remained intact, with no cyanosis noted. Patient was able to talk normally after a few minutes. Her pulse improved and was strong (+2) about 5 minutes after the epinephrine injection.  911 was called and paramedics arrived about 5 minutes later. Patient was taken away by the paramedics to the hospital, stable and in good condition.

Patient received her Janssen COVID vaccine and was sitting in a chair in the conference room when she slumped over in her chair and became unresponsive. Patient had just received her one dose Janssen vaccine and was sitting in a chair approximately 3-5 minutes after receiving the vaccine.  She began to slump over in her chair and was unresponsive. Two RNs responded to assess the patient. Patients feet were elevated and ice packs applied to her neck and axillary areas. Patient was breathing and had a pulse. Patient responded to her name once and then passed out again. Patient was unable to respond after this.  Her eyes were open.  Patient was lifted into a wheelchair by three nurses and brought to a private area.  Patient was warm and sweat was running down her face.  Her sweater was removed and ice packs again were applied to her neck and axillary area.  Patient continued to have a pulse and was breathing.  EMS was called.  Patient slowly began to come around and could answer questions after about 5 minutes of being unresponsive. She was confused and had no memory of what had occurred. She reported feeling light headed and seeing spots in her vision.  She continued to feel light headed. EMS assessed patient.  Vitals were stable and blood sugar was WDL.  Patient reported feeling much better. She denied feeling light headed or dizzy any longer.  She was able to answer all questions asked.  Patient did not want to go to the hospital and refused transport to the hospital via ambulance. She was observed for an additional 20-30 minutes at which time her boss arrived to pick her up. She was educated on calling 911 if she began to feel light headed or dizzy again. Patient verbalized understanding. She was walked to the car by an RN.

Patient notified Vaccine Coordinator on 4/7/2021 that when she received her first dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 2/3/2021, she had immediate sharp pain while the vaccine was being injected into her right arm.  She stated that the injection site remained extremely painful and that she was not able to use her arm for the next 2 days, and only had slight improvement in range of motion over the next week.  She received her second dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 3/4/2021 and did not have the same immediate pain in her left arm, but reported she didn?t even feel the vaccine being administered.  She stated that she had some minor general arm soreness in her left arm after the two days following administration of 2nd dose, and then it resolved and did not interfere with her range of motion or use of her left arm.  She scheduled an appointment with her primary Medical Doctor to check on her right arm, and had an appointment on 4/2/2021.  Her primary MD ordered an MRI of her right arm/shoulder, which was completed on 4/5/2021.  She told Vaccine Coordinator that she will have a follow up consult with an Orthopedist and will need Physical Therapy for her right arm.  She is confident this will resolve with time and therapy and was not upset, but stated she would rather deal with a sore arm than with contracting COVID-19 disease.  Vaccine Coordinator did recommend that she also fill out a VAERS report with details concerning her symptoms.

Patient felt light-headed, then became unresponsive. He moved both arms halfway up, and they both quivered simultaneously. I called for help. One nurse raised his legs & another put a pulse oximeter on patient & took his BP. Patient started responding to verbal cues. A nurse gave him Gatorade to start drinking. He was drenched in sweat from head to feet. The nurse continued to take his BP, which did hit 120/~70, but then dipped again. Once his BP & pulse stabilized, he was able to go home. Patient ate a full meal & a non-diet soda. He reported being exhausted ~4 pm. He fell asleep & rose once to urinate.  Dr. at a Family Medicine practice checked his heart and lungs, and confirmed this did not appear to be an allergic reaction, but more likely was a vagovasal reaction. Patient started reacting ~10 minutes after the injection.

I am current diabetic and have a recent history (1 year ago) of muscular dystrophy. I use a cane to assist with mobility, and cannot lift my legs far to go up high stairs, nor lift my arms past my chest as a baseline.   Later in the evening/middle of the night, after the second shot, I got up around 3:30am to use the rest room and after each step, my knees, legs, hips, and arms gave out,  falling forward on my face and head. I had no strength to catch myself from falling, nor could I lift myself at all. Initially, I could not even roll over. It took 10 minutes with help from my wife to roll over, but I remained on the floor. I was on the bathroom floor/snake crawling for 2 hours trying to figure out ways I can get up, but I had no strength at all. After snake crawling to the bedroom, my wife called the paramedics to get me up at 530am, Tuesday April 6th.    Later that night of the 6th I did a little better, with help  I could sit up in the bed.  Overnight I tried to lift up to stand, and barely could stand, but my legs were too shaky, body bruised of course, and weak.   April 7th, the next day, I was able to sit up. Later that day I was able to get up to go to the bathroom with my wife?s help and the use of a rolling walker with wheels, brakes and a seat, about 3:50am this morning.  I have 35-40% of my strength, and can sit on the side of the bed. I need assistance to the bathroom and I have a ways to go to recover to my baseline.

I asked her to stay down and relax. patient was asked if she was aware of where she was and time and she responded properly. Then she mentioned she has had panic attacks previously. Emergency services was notified immediately and Market director.  Patients vitals were taken and her blood pressure started at 135/95 mmHg 85 hr. 5 minutes later her vitals were done to 127/87 mmHg 82 hr.  By the time, emergency services arrived she was sitting done on her chair and feeling much better. She refused Emergency services. She sat in the observation room for 20 minutes after and was checked on by the pharmacist. She was stable and in good spirit when she left.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 1 AM on 4/3/21, I got up to take some Tylenol since I woke up feeling like I had a temperature.  I walked to the kitchen (which isn't very far) and had an extreme feeling of overwhelming weakness and fainted. (only fainted one other time in my life).  I hit my head and eye and now have bruising from my hairline and down my cheek on my right side.  My eye and eye lid are  black and blue.  I had 101 temp and chills and body aches.  Immediately starting vomiting and had diarrhea for 6 hours.  Had a temp of 100 the whole day of 4/3/21.  Then 99.5 on 4/4 and 4/5/21 and still tired and achy.  By 4/6, I felt better.  Although my symptoms were just a few days, I would have never taken the second Moderna shot, in hindsight.  In fact, lots of people I know have had strong reactions to the second Moderna vaccine.  I have to say I have never gotten so sick so fast in my life.  No way to fight it - I felt took weak and vulnerable.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: procedure in which his heart was cut from top to bottom/pacemaker dependent; fast heart rate; afib; red dots on both of his arms; rash on both arms; dizzy; sick; very weak/no energy; hard time walking; cannot do the simplest of tasks; flutter; A spontaneous report was received from a Consumer concerning herself, a 57-year-old male patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced the events, fast heart rate, cardiac pacemaker dependent, atrial fibrillation, red dots on both of his arms, rash on both arms, dizziness, sick, Atrial flutter, very weak and no energy, hard time walking, and cannot do the simplest of tasks.  The patient's medical history included atrial fibrillation and had a pacemaker placed about 8-9 months ago.  Products known to have been used by the patient, within two weeks prior to the event were blood pressure medication, antiarrhythmics.  On 01 Mar 2021, prior to the onset of events, the patient received their first of the two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 030m20a) via unknown route for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  On 01 Mar 2021, after vaccination, the patient developed red dots on both of his arms. For next two days, the patient had rash on both arms, was dizzy, felt sick, developed fast heart rate; went to hospital twice for heart rate either 07 Mar 2021 or 13 Mar 2021.During first visit to hospital, fast rate was brought under control, while in the second visit, the patient had a procedure in which his heart was cut from top to bottom and was made pacemaker dependent. The atrial fibrillation could not be controlled for 26 hours and had a flutter which was not identified and could not be controlled. Flutter returned after stopping amlodipine and hence patient was restarted on amlodipine. The patient now feels very weak, has a hard time walking, has no energy, cannot do the simplest of tasks, still experiences fast heart rate and flutter every now and then.   No Laboratory investigations were provided. The Treatment information included pacemaker, amlodipine.  Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not provided.  The outcome of the events, fast heart rate, cardiac pacemaker dependent, atrial fibrillation, red dots on both of his arms, rash on both arms, dizziness, sick, atrial flutter, very weak and no energy, hard time walking, cannot do the simplest of tasks were unknown.

Within 30-60 seconds of receiving the vaccine my heart started racing. No other symptoms. I alerted the nurse - she took my blood pressure and it was very high (XXX/110). EMTs were called in case I was having an allergic reaction, but I did not have any other symptoms of allergies, just a very high BP and heart rate. At this point I'm sure anxiety drove my BP higher, on top of the reaction, since I was concerned I was going to go into anaphylaxis, but the original racing heart started within one minute of the injection while I was beginning my 15 minute wait time near the injection station. I worked on regulating my breathing and with the EMTs monitoring, my BP down to a manageable but still elevated rate after about 20 minutes. I did not go to the hospital. Once I was resting at home it took about 4 hours before I felt my heart rate was at a normal level and the feeling of racing was gone.  I did not have any other adverse reactions until 4/7/2021 which is the first day that the injection site (upper L arm) started aching.
LAB_DATA: BP and EKG on site. I am scheduling a follow up with a Doctor this week.
HISTORY: Ulcerative colitis - in remission over 5 years Chronic lower back and sciatic pain (Hydrocodone & Methocarbamol taken as needed, not taken on day of vaccination)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Prior to recieving her vaccine , the patient stated she was nervous and has anxiety.  After recieving the vaccine she said she felt fine. I told her to stay there for few minutes make sure she was ok. Her husband was getting the vaccine next so I went to start reviewing his paperwork. 5 minutes later he said she didnt feel good. She said she felt like she was going to pass out and wanted to sit or lay down on the floor. Her husband and I helped lower her to the ground and she lay on her side. I asked if she wanted water or anything she said yes. I got her a cold water and she put it against her forehead and said she just needed a minute.   After 10 minutes she got up and sat in the chair and said she felt better.  I then gave her husband his vaccine.   10 minutes later as they wanted after his he said she did not feel well again. She was laying on the floor and said she did not feel like she woulf pass out but just didnt feel right. I asked if she wanted me to call 911 she said yes, just to be checked out.  They came with in 5 minutes and then she said she felt better and was sitting again.   They talked to her and watched her stand up. They checked her pulse and said it was normal and her color was good. She ended up not going with the ambulance and agreed it was probably jsut anxiety  / panic attack.  She walked away fine and also stated she needed to eat dinner.

It has been constant, no pulses, no frequency changes, etc.  Just constant high pitch ringing in both ears. Sometimes by inner ear feels funny, slightly tingle feeling that is related to the tinnitus.  The tinnitus is most noticeable in quiet settings, sleeping, reading, watching TV, I do not noticed it as much in office environments, listening to music, walking outside.  I have experienced tinnitus in the past after loud music band or rock concert but do not attend live loud music often and try to avoid it because it hurts my ears.  I do not have any known hearing problem, I try to protect my ears and use hearing protection often to avoid damage. When I cut my lawn I wear hearing protection, when I am working on shop floor I wear hearing protection.  I am thinking the vaccine is related somehow. I never had COVID-19 in past.  I use to be able to be in quiet settings and not have any tinnitus before vaccine.

It was reported to me by the pharmacist who was on duty on April 6, 2021 that the patient presented to the pharmacy on April 6, 2021 for her COVID-19 vaccination and was anxious prior to the appointment. The patient stated that immediately after receiving the vaccination, she felt a shooting pain in the injection site. The patient stated that within a few minutes, she felt lightheaded and nauseous. The patient then stated that within 20 minutes, she felt like she was having an asthma attack and had to use her rescue inhaler (albuterol HFA). It was reported that the patient left the pharmacy about 45 minutes after receiving the vaccination and the patient stated she was feeling better. The patient the reported to the pharmacy that the morning of April 7, 2021 that her symptoms of shortness of breath and wheezing returned and she went to an emergency room for treatment. The patient stated that after admission into the ER, the medical staff performed two EKGs and one chest X-ray, which were unremarkable. The patient stated she received treatment with Duoneb because she was wheezing and and treatment with IV methylprednisolone because her throat and tongue appeared swollen. The patient stated she was discharged on April 7, 2021 and was prescribed albuterol solution for nebulization and prednisone 10 mg tablets.

I have always had relatively heavy periods due to my diagnosis of VonWillebrand's disease.  Four days after receiving the vaccine, my cycle came on early and I had heavier bleeding than I have ever experienced with large clots.  The bleeding slowed down, but lasted for an entire month.   My cycle then returned to normal.  It seemed very coincidental that this happened immediately following the vaccine, and was not normal for me at all.  I recently read similar stories of other women reporting this, so while at the time it was concerning, I did not report it.  I am a firm believer in science and thought this was possibly just a fluke, but felt that after reading many stories of women having a similar experience, that the responsible action is to report this, to ensure that all of the data is being studied, since the vaccine is so new.  That being said, I only had mild side effects from the vaccine, and I am very grateful that I was able to receive the vaccine, as I have known quite a few people that have died from COVID.  This bleeding for me was not dangerous at any time, and while I was a bit faint, the bleeding during the course of the month did slow down and this all resolved.  Therefore, I would still get the vaccine again.  I should note that after my second vaccine, I had a few days of spotting outside of my cycle, which resolved as well.  I have had no issues since.

48 yo female who presented today for her first dose of the Moderna vaccine. Vaccine was administered at 1400 in the left deltoid. Patient was directed to go to the observation area for a 15 minute observation period after administration of her Moderna vaccine. While walking, patient was assisted to the floor by two volunteers, amid a suspected seizure. Arriving on scene, patient was unconscious and having a tonic-clonic seizure that lasted 20 seconds. EMT's were on scene placing an 18g PIV in the right forearm, collecting a BG, and had placing the patient on the monitor. Patient was placed on a NRB mask at 15 L of O2. Patient again fell unconscious and had a second tonic-clonic seizure that lasted 20 seconds.    Patient regained consciousness and requested that provider unlock cell phone to collect patient medication list and husband's information. Husband was contacted and requested to enter to be by her side. Husband reported a history of seizures (tonic clonic) and current treatment/management. He requested that patient not to be taken to the ER. Provider advised husband and patient that the paramedics would determine the necessity of her transfer to the ER.    Ambulance was notified and Fire reported to the patient's side by 1435. Upon arrival, husband and patient requested not to be transferred to the ER. While answering questions, patient again was assisted to the floor and sustained a third tonic-clonic seizure lasting approximately 20 seconds. Provider aided paramedics in transferring patient to the gurney. Patient was transferred to hospital with husband and all personal belongings.

She had no history of anaphylaxis from any cause, she had no history of reactions to vaccines or components.  After about 5 minutes I checked on her and she said she was feeling very dizzy.  I called management for assistance and got her ice packs for neck and forehead. I took her blood pressure and it was 150/90, HR 73. We laid her down and elevated her legs.  She said that she felt some pressure in her chest but she had pulled a muscle there the day before and wasn't sure if it was related.  She said the room was spinning as she continued to lay on the ground and it was not improving.  Her blood pressure was taken about 5 minutes later and it was 143/85 HR 73.  She said it is usually low.   She had no signs of local reaction, hives, or swelling.  She complained of nausea.  After a few more minutes she said she was not feeling any better and was having pain in her throat and difficulty breathing.  I asked her to try to take a deep breath and she was gasping for air, unable to breathe deeply.  I administered epinephrine (one dose) and called 911.  I rechecked blood pressure while waiting for paramedics and it was 125/80.  She was taken to hospital when they arrived.  Her mom arrived shortly before the ambulance and went with her.  Pt never lost consciousness.  Management followed up with patient this evening and patient is home and well, but the ER did classify the event as an allergic reaction.

It is always present, but worse when I sit in a reclining or lying down position.  Other flu like symptoms went away  about 48 hours after the vaccine was administered. The vertigo lingers. Trying any sort of doctor recommended maneuvers makes it much worse and triggers nausea and vomiting.
LAB_DATA: I had vestibular testing about 2 weeks ago and am awaiting test results, though I was told that nothing significant showed up in the tests. I had hearing testing about 3 weeks ago and that was normal too.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received Moderna vaccine. She told pharmacist in IMZ room that she was very nervous about getting the shot and felt nauseous. When patient went and sat down we noticed that it looked like she was crying. I went out to check on her and patient stated that she felt very nauseous and like she could not take a deep breath. I gave patient water and benadryl (10 ml of 12.5 mg/5 ml solution) and told her to take deep breaths in through the nose and out through the mouth. Within 30 seconds to 1 minute of taking the benadryl patient was feeling fine and able to breath normally again. on the morning of the 9th (3:00 am approx.) I woke up with the back of my left elbow itching and there were welts there.  It spread to my other elbow and to the inside of my knees.  I went to Urgent Care in and was given a steroid shot and prescribed a round of steroid pills.  Took as directed.  However, by the 13th (Saturday), I was much worse as the hives had spread to my stomach and up and down both legs and arms.  Received a second steroid shot and completed the steroid pills.  Was off all medication and supplements beginning March 18th due to a scheduled colonoscopy on the 25th.  Prior to my second COVID shot on the 21st, the hives began to abate.  However, on the same day as the second COVID shot, the hives worsened.  I was unable to take any medication because of the colonoscopy and had scheduled an appointment with the allergist.  I only used oatmeal soap, cortisone cream, and itch defense lotion  to attempt to alleviate my symptoms.  I am now taking Zyrtec in the morning and two doxepin 25MG each evening.  That is working and the welts have abated.  One interesting side effect of all this is I am no longer gluten intolerant - I'm not complaining.
OTHER_MEDS: Zyrtec, Flonase, calcium, magnesium, collagen, turmeric, biotin, fish oil

The next morning I was still itching, seemed a little red on my hands. Went to work, and the itching started bad again, took one more Benadryl at noon, it didn?t help much. In the span of a half hour or so I became covered with itchy red hives all over, even up into my hair. I went to urgent care at 6:30 pm. They didn?t seem surprised when I said I had my first vaccine dose, as they have seen multiple other patients with the same symptoms. They gave me 2 Benadryl and two prednisone tablets, and a prescription for both plus famotodine. 10 prednisone, two a day for The next five days, plus 2 Benadryl every six hours, and one famotodine Twice a day. EMT arrived at 7 pm,  he explained to patient that she would not be charged since patient was nervous of the charges that might be imposed to her. He performed assessment and VS: BP 154/101, HR 98, O2 Sat 100% RA, RR 20, patient stated her tingling and numbness sensation on her left arm was gone and she would not want to be escorted to the hospital for further assessment and treatment. Patent signed the form for further treatment with EMT staff. Patient was able to ambulate with steady gait without any issues with her husband to the parking lot. As expected from any vaccine I've received, I have a sore arm that is lasting over 3 days (again, this is expected). What I wasn't quite expecting: -Fever at 101 for 48 hours -Extreme fatigue for 48 hours -Alternating chills and hot flashes/sweating for 48 hours -Quite strong aches and pains (hurt to lay down, sit, stand, just existing hurt) for 48 hours -Headache for 48 hours -Itchy/sore throat around the 24 hour mark, lasting to the 36 hour mark from time of injection  Treatment: I took 400 mg of Ibuprofen around the 12 hour mark from vaccination (about 5 hours after fever spiked at 101--fever rose no higher than 101). I continued 400 mg of Ibuprofen the next morning and once more that same evening (two does of 400 mg Ibuprofen). Each of those doses brought fever down to around 99 for about 4 hours, and I felt considerably better (though definitely still quite sick--just not contained-to-lying-in-bed sick). I took 200 mg of Ibuprofen around the 36 hour mark, and that was it. Fever then back to normal range (approx 98) and feeling 95%-100% recovered all day.  Obviously none of those are life-threatening, but they sure knocked me out. Definitely way worse than the "mild" symptoms advertised. I'm definitely not complaining, as I'm overjoyed to now be vaccinated, and I'm so grateful for the scientific community, the CDC, and you people reading this right now for all your work in making it happen, and doing it as safely as possible. Thank you!

Muscular soreness in injection site starting a couple/few hours after injection, persisting 30 hours later. Soreness is not extraordinary. It is no worse than soreness from a workout and it radiates out no greater than 2 inches from injection site. No noticeable discoloration of the skin near the injection site. No rash. Starting in the morning prior to afternoon vaccination I developed a headache. I drank caffeine and a lot of water so I presume it was not caffeine withdrawal or dehydration.  The night before I moved a large number of heavy boxes in my garage.  Pain appeared to originate in back of neck, likely muscle strain induced headache. I did not want to take advil prior to the vaccination.  After surviving the day with a headache I took two advil (normal adult dosage) around 7pm or so. Last night around 8pm - 8:30pm (approximately 5 - 5 1/2 hours after injection) I began feeling the onset of a low grade fever.  Confirmed low grade fever using digital thermometer in both ears/multiple readings.  Low temperature 99.0/high temperature 99.2. Low grade fever felt like it subsided after about an hour to hour and a half.  Did not retake temperature. Has not recurred. I AM PROVIDING THIS INFORMATION SOLELY TO PROVIDE DATA FOR THIS NEW VACCINE. ORDINARILY I WOULD NOT EXPECT TO REPORT SOMETHING LIKE THIS.
OTHER_MEDS: Testosterone - daily, but none applied on day of vaccination. Testosterone is normally applied topically to upper arms (i.e. anticipated injection site)
ALLERGIES: Severe allergy to Penicillin as a child. Apparent food intolerance to tomatoes and/or onions.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day after my second dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine, I had sudden onset tinnitus in both ears. It persists one week later. Never louder, never softer. Always there. No OTC medicine helps. The noise level is moderate (6 out of 10). I also have stuffy sinuses since the vaccination, but relieving sinus pressure using cold medicine does not stop the tinnitus. My blood pressure is now measuring "low hypertension," whereas before it was reliably normal. The soonest an ENT doctor can see me is in 3 weeks. I'm very concerned about possible hearing loss, but at this time, I would guess any hearing loss is mild.
LAB_DATA: None to-date. Hope to see an ENT soon, but earliest appointment I could get is April 26.

On Wednesday April 7, 2021 client received her second dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine (LOT # ER8729, EXP 7/2021) at approximately 3:45pm. During assessment questions, client stated she had a "mild reaction" to her first Pfizer dose after 15 minutes in the Observation Area and a history of a weakened immune system. At 4:05pm, client report to EMT Peuvion of "minor tightness" in her throat. Per EMT Peuvion report, client was observed to have minor flushing and splotching on her hands. Lead RN was notified and authorized 50mg of Diphenhydramine HCL oral solution per protocol be given with a water bottle. Initial vitals were taken at 4:07pm: BP: 120/70, HR: 72, RR: 16, lungs: clear bilaterally. Vitals were reassessed at 4:15pm: BP: 134/74, HR: 82, RR: 16, lungs: clear bilaterally. Client stated her initial throat tightness had subsided. Vitals were reassessed 4:25 and remained stable and normal: BP: 124/68, HR: 74, RR 16, O2 sat: 94%. Patient was alert and oriented x4 during entire interaction. No further interventions indicated. Client was advised that if new symptoms develop or current symptoms worsen to seek emergency care. Client was further educated by Lead RN & EMT on signs and symptoms of adverse reactions and when to go to the ED/call MD. Client was also encouraged to sign-up on v-safe. Client left vaccination site at approximately 3:45pm with a steady gait.
PRIOR_VAX: Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine
ALLERGIES: Mild allergic reaction to first Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Joints began feeling achy and body felt tired within a few hours of vaccination. About 10 hours later body began to feel warm and then within an hour began uncontrollable shivers and aching in testicles followed shortly after by a throbbing headache and pain behind eyeballs. I put on extra clothing and jumped into bed as symptoms persisted. Later in the night I began sweating profusely and removed the clothing. The headache and pain behind the eyes persisted. I also began feeling nauseous and almost vomited when I went to the bathroom. My body was so tired and achy I could barely move. I tried to wake up for work but my headache and pain behind the eyes was so bad I went back to bed for another four hours. I did not have any appetite for the rest of the day.  My headache subsided that afternoon and I went for a walk that night and my body still felt incredibly tired and achy. The pain behind my eyes persisted. The following day I felt somewhat better and could work. That night I went for a jog and my body felt extremely heavy, my joints ached, and I could not catch my breath. My symptoms continued to improve but I have had no sex drive for a week.
PRIOR_VAX: small pox

The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. Patient had no known allergies. Prior to vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. Patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. Patient did not receive any other medications within 2 weeks of vaccination.  On 21Mar2021 at 07:30 PM, after receiving his first dose, he began noticing facial drooping, which began to intensify, on the right side. He was advised by a medical professional to immediately call an ambulance and he was then taken to an emergency room where received a CT scan and full bloodwork on Mar2021. Luckily, the facial palsy began to subside and he was able to return home after the test results came back and a stroke was ruled out - it was stated that this was some kind of immuno-reaction to the vaccine. He still felt as though his face was still not 100% back to normal and still felt a bit droopy (noticeable in the mirror) yet it does feel better than on 21Mar2021 evening. Patient had a nasal swab on 22Mar2021 with negative result. One of the reporters is a psychologist and reported that her son received Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine. Psychologist asking about risk of Bell's palsy, incidence, and outcomes and if these patients received their second dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine. She read about 7 cases of Bell's palsy in a Dec2020 article in the [Redacted], 4 of them on the Pfizer vaccine. The reporter further clarified and described that at 6pm (2 hours after dose), patient reported he felt fine and was happy he got the vaccine; but then sometime after that, he reported "strange feelings in face" and then eyes started drooping and then mouth started drooping, all on right side of face. They called the university clinic and was instructed to go to ER. Brain scans and blood work were done; they ruled out stroke and said it was a possible reaction to the vaccine. He was discharged at midnight and by then, paralysis was 80-85% resolved. He is an otherwise very healthy young man. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Headache, soreness in arm, stomachache that lasted 3 days

My vaccine was administered at 12:30pm. I waited until 12:55 at CVS after the vaccine to make sure there were no reactions. I also move my arm around a lot after the injection to keep it from hurting. I drove home, at lunch and about 2:45 was hit with a very noticeable headache. I never get headaches and eat healthy and consume about a gallon of water a day. I knew it wasn't from dehydration or being hungry.  Headache was in the temple area and made my eyes hurt in the same way they would if you had cried for an extended period of time or were overtired. At 3pm a wave of exhaustion hit me. I was sitting working trying to combat the headache and felt almost wiped out. I got through the rest of my work day (4:30) and went to lay down immediately. I passed out almost instantly until 7 pm. I work up and showered, ate dinner and started to feel a little warm. It should be noted it was an unseasonably warm day and got up to 77, so it was a tiny bit warm in my home. I put on loose fitting clothes and slayed on the couch still with the bad headache and the injection site started to throb so I placed and ice pack on for 20 minutes. I could only stay awake until 8:45 and got in bed. I could not get comfortable for several hours feeling very warm. I tried a fan on high and drinking more water but i felt very warm like how you feel with the flu. I took my temp at 1130pm it was normal. I continued to toss and turn and feel very warm and slightly dizzy, in the sense that I hadn't been able to sleep and with the headache my body was just exhausted. Around 2 am i woke up for more water and got in the shower because I had sweated so much my sheets were wet and my clothes. I got out of the shower around 10 minutes later, changed and got new sheets and got back in bad. Around 330 I felt very hot again and opened the windows and got another ice pack for my arm which was throbbing again. I finally fell asleep after 3:45am. I got up for work at 6am. I felt slightly foggy, and very hot. But no fever. My temp is normally around 97.4-97.9 and it was 98.4. Still normal but I was running warmer than usual. It took a long time to get ready and despite hot water in the shower I was freezing. i got dress and debated going to work. Got in the car at 6:45 and my drive to work is 30 minutes. 1/2 way into my drive I got very sweaty again and went home to change my clothes because they were too warm. Got to work around 7:20 and still felt warm but they take our temps at the door and min was still okay, no fever. I drank a lot of water and ate, and at 8:30 am all of a sudden the exhaustion was gone and I felt normal. I got home form work at 5:30p and took a 3 hour nap and felt normal again.

Approximately 54 hours after receiving shot I noticed a couple hives on the lower portion of my body.  I didn't think much of it and went to bed around 10pm.  I woke up around 1am on 3/20 and noticed that my lips were very swollen and I had several hives on the lower half of my body.  Additionally my scrotum was enlarged.  Other than the physical symptoms I felt fine - no fever, body aches, pain, or respiratory issues.  I decided to go back to bed after taking 2 Advil.  I woke up at 7am and was still having a reaction so I decided to go to the ER.  While at the ER the gave me steroid and Benadryl which immediately started working to reduce the reaction.  They took blood work which came back "essentially perfect" according to the Dr.  I was discharged and prescribed an epipen, and a steroid which i took for two days.  I was instructed to follow up with my primary care physician which I did on 3/26.  The ER Dr believed that my reaction was caused by something that i had ate; however, to the best of my knowledge, I am NOT allergic to any foods.  Shortly before the reaction I had eaten a can of ravioli and some bread.  The can from a 12 pack that we bought at the grocery store approximately 6 months ago.  It as the last can in the pack and I did not have a reaction to any of the previous cans.  I met with my family Dr's PA the following week and she indicated that while there is no way to know with 100% confidence that the reaction was from the shot, she noted that it was highly unlikely that my reaction was from the ravioli can.  The PA informed me that I needed to use extra caution should I decide to get the second shot.  I am scheduled to receive the second shot on 4/14.
LAB_DATA: blood work collected on 3/19 at Hospital.
ALLERGIES: None.  Never had an allergic reaction prior to this event.

After receiving the second injection in my left arm on Thursday (4/1/21) afternoon, I noticed painful swelling had developed in my (L) armpit lymph node on Friday (4/2/21). Naproxen sodium taken orally (1-2x/day) & CBD oil lightly applied to area (2-3x/day) helped to lessen pain. Swelling began to dissipate daily & was undetectable by Sunday. On either Sunday (4/4/21) or Monday (4/5/21), I noticed some slight menstrual breakthrough bleeding. It was not the correct time in my cycle for menstruation and spotting is highly irregular - I have never experienced this. At first, I thought this was completely random & unattributed to receiving the vaccine but saw on social media that many other women had experienced these effects after their shot. They also spoke of increased pain and heavy bleeding. As I haven't yet had my period again, I cannot comment on my experience at this time, but I am still experiencing the light breakthrough bleeding. I also noticed some slight fatigue through Monday evening (4/5/21).

He got the vaccine, started to get the headache within 45 minutes, ran some errands and after a couple of hours he felt like something was burning on his buttock, and noticed a really bad red rash on the left side on the left cheek from the crack outward. It was extremely hot to the touch and very sore, kind of throbbing and swollen and progressively got worse. He was just not feeling well, nauseous and dizzy and went to sleep but when he woke up it had spread to the other cheek. It looks like he got burned or scalded red/purple in color. He has no reaction on the arm itself, but only on the buttock and a blistery, blood red, leathery feeling rash/blotch on his entire buttock to both hips on both sides. It is difficult for him to sit. He also had headache, the muscle pain, joint pain, chills, nausea.  He did not vomit but had not eaten anything. He has had a high fever up to 103 until this morning 4/8/21 which is about 99-100.  He woke up soaking wet today. He has not been able to turn his neck, and not able to lift his arm above his waist level since the vaccine, and not able to turn his neck to the left at all. He can turn it 5-10 degrees, but right is okay. He took some Benadryl over the last 2 days for the reaction but it has not. He also has taken aspirin/Aleve for the fever. He was so sock and had no energy and could not sleep but could not keep his eyes open either, was not able to open them. He did write his doctor when the rash was only on one side, which they did not give him any advice as he was not feeling any worse at that time. He was at 101 fever throughout the day and then at night went to 102. He was hoping that the rash would be better, but actually worse as described above. He has not had any appetite, trying to drink fluids but made him nauseous, and he normally drinks water all day long. His normal temp is 97.7. He has been taking showers to try and keep his fevers down and the water hitting the rash feels like somebody is pouring scolding water on it. He did call Moderna on 4/6/21 asking if this was a reaction that anybody has reported, and he is waiting for somebody to call him back.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 09MAR2021-Patient is a 87 y.o. old female with a history of receiving her second COVID vaccine this past Friday.  For the previous 2 to 3 days she has had increasing fatigue and generalized weakness.  Anorexia and nausea have been noted as well.  Apparently has not been eating or drinking well at all.  No vomiting or diarrhea.  No new medication recently.  No fever or chills. Patient was seen and evaluated in the ER tonight by the ER physician.  Significant acute renal failure was noted.  Urinalysis was unrevealing.  Mild hyperkalemia and moderate metabolic acidosis were noted as well.  Initial treatment in the emergency room included a 1 L bolus of normal saline and antiemetic therapy.  The hospitalist service was then consulted for admission."   Discharge Summary Written 20MAR2021-Patient was admitted and started on IV fluids.  Nephrology was consulted.  She was started on a bicarb drip for metabolic acidosis.  Renal US was negative for hydronephrosis but with incidental biliary ductal dilatation which was stable compared to a previous imaging study in 2011.  Unfortunately her renal function continued to worsen and require dialysis.  She had a temporary dialysis catheter placed on 3/12.  She had RRT started on 3/12 and again on 3/13.  Her urine output, electrolytes, and azotemia started to improve slowly.  Renal function continued to improve and she no longer required any RRT.  Her temporary dialysis catheter was removed on 3/19.  Her Foley catheter was also removed on 3/19 and she was urinating well prior to discharge.  She will go home with oral Lasix.  Patient felt much improved and is agreeable for discharge on this date- 20MAR2021  Second Admission- 02APR2021-05APR2021- INDICATION FOR ADMISSION:   This is an 87-year-old female with history of COPD, hypertension, and chronic lung disease, who presented to the Emergency Department on April 2, 2021 with a chief complaint of shortness of breath..  Three days prior to this admission the patient had increasing shortness of breath.  The patient also had a nonproductive cough but denied any fever or chills.  The patient was started on IV Lasix and IV steroids in the ED.  She also had elevated BNP. She was admitted to the hospital for further medical management.   Discharge Summary Written 05APR2021- She was started on IV steroids, IV Lasix, nebulization, and she was monitored closely.  The patient also had HGB dropping to 8.8 from 11.3 back in March 2021.  The patient was started on proton pump inhibitor. Gastroenterology and cardiology eventually were consulted to see the patient.  She did have an EGD done at this time which showed gastritis.  She will continue Protonix for now.  She was started on IV Lasix and she improved with the treatment.  Now she remains on room air.  She denied any respiratory issue.  Her renal function still remains at baseline.  Today creatinine is 1.5.  The patient can be discharged home today and continue oral Lasix at home daily for now.  She was instructed to follow up with her primary care physician and also her cardiologist as outpatient in 1 to 2 weeks.
LAB_DATA: Admission-09MAR2021- BUN 87, CREAT 6.9, K 5.5, EGFR 4.9 Discharge Date- 20MAR2021- BUN 69, CREAT 3.5, EGFR 11.2, K 4.2

Patient came to the receptionist's desk shortly after recieving his vaccination stating his abdomen felt "tight."  With further questioning by provider, he also endorsed feeling slightly lightheaded and dizzy.  He was moved to an exam room for examiniation and monitoring.  Patient found to be bradycardic but otherwise normal vitals (108/70, HR 56, T 97.5, O2 98%).  Patient slightly pale.  Patient given water and offered a snack which he declined.   Patient later reported he had experienced this same abdominal sensation earlier in the day prior to vaccination.  Described as "tight" and "like something's in there that needs to come out."  Denied history of constipation or recent GI illness including nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea.  During his vasovagal response, he was unclear if he felt nauseated; at one time he thought he might feel a bit nauseated but then later denied nausea.  No emesis occurred. Patient was monitored for ~30 minutes and released to go home with his spouse when he was feeling better (resolution of lightheadedness/dizziness).  He was given ER precautions and instructed to call his PCP in the morning if his abdomen still felt tight.  A clinic nurse was asked to follow the patient home to ensure he arrived without incidence, and no adverse event occurred between the clinic and his house.  Patient was called the following morning and reported he felt better with resolution of his abdominal tightness.
HISTORY: Patient reports history of hypotension.  Otherwise unknown.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 8 minutes after the shot I started to feel "off" which progressed into lightheadedness and thought I was going to pass out. I alerted the pharmacy team right about the 10-minute mark when they increased instead of getting better. Had to sit down, hard to form thoughts, hard to talk without feeling nauseous. Got very hot, had to remove the top layer I was wearing, and put my head down in my hands bc I felt like I was going to get sick. Then around 11:05, the hot flashes turned into a cold sweat, still with the pass out/nausea feeling. Around 11:08 my lower back and hands felt like they were shaking but they weren't. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I knew my arm would hurt.  But the day after my first shot I started off with cold sweats, drenched in sweat. Really hot, then by 9 am I was very cold, chills, felt like I was running a fever, but checked several times and was not running a fever.  Body aches started soon after I got cold, joints aches and then just plain throbbed and hurt.  The headache was not sever but was present all day. I couldn't lift my arm when I work up that morning, it remained like a lead wait till today 4/8/21 when I woke up.  I felt exhausted and had bouts of vertigo on and off all day 4/7/21.  Felt nauseas.  Neck was stiff.  My muscles were stiff and sore like I just ran a marathon.   I feel 100% better today 4/8/21 but the day after my shot on 4/7/21 I was down for the count and I couldn't function normally.  I felt like I had a lead blanket weighing me down.  I hope I will get a super human power.   I will get my 2nd dose but I worry if it will be worse than the first.  Oh and I am extremely hungry and craving sweets (which will make me fat btw).   I talked to friends who also had the same reaction, didn't call my doctor.  Thinking this might be normal for women and the moderna shot.    I am reporting to have my voice be heard.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After onset at 6:45, fever rapidly increased to over 102 by 8pm.  Muscle aches and soreness accompanied fever.  Very thirsty.  Fever stayed near 103 overnight until I took tylenol somewhere between 2-4 am.  By 5 am the fever was down to 101.5.  Fever stayed between 101-102 most of the following day (4/6/2021), dropping to 99.5-100 around  6pm.  Stayed low grade under 100 through the night and was back to normal by the morning of 4/7/2021.  I felt mostly normal on 4/7/2021 aside from severe muscle tightness in gluts, hamstrings, and thighs, with soreness in my lower back (unknown if that is related to the vaccine, but it was not present before 4/7/2021).  Today, 4/8/2021 the muscle tightness & soreness remains but the fever is still gone and I feel otherwise normal.
OTHER_MEDS: B12 monthly injection Latanoprost once/day one drop each eye
ALLERGIES: Augmentin; contact allergies to BHT, PolyEthylene Glycol, many fragrances

Because of my celiac condition, I avoid eating products with wheat and gluten in them. However, occasionally it is unavoidable, such as with traveling. Typical reactions include fatigue, headache, mild brain fog, irritability, and watery bowel movements for up to 3 days following ingestion. However, since receiving the Moderna vaccine I have encountered wheat products 3 times; in all three cases the reaction was much more severe and included whole-body ache for 5-7 days, insomnia for 2-3 days, dry heaving for 24 hours, extreme sensitivity to motion/motion sickness for up to 3 days, intense gastrointestinal discomfort for up to 7 days, constipation and diarrhea, severe congestion, shortness of breath, elevated heart rate, confusion or disorientation, and an overall elevated level of symptoms lasting from 4-7 days depending on the amount ingested.
OTHER_MEDS: Multivitamin OTC Vitamin D, B Complex, Calcium, Magnesium

Pt left facility with steady gait at 1218 with family.
